another example.

Count nouns, mass nouns and their
transformations: a unified category-theoretic
semantics
\url{https://marieetgonzalo.files.wordpress.com/1999/06/mnmac1.pdf}

adjunction between a category CN CN of count nouns and a category MN MN of mass nouns:
â€¢ \bullet The morphisms in these categories are relationships like â€œa man is a human,â€ resp. â€œwater is liquid.â€
â€¢ \bullet The left adjoint is pluralization: if â€œa dogâ€ is a count noun, then â€œdogsâ€ is a mass noun.
â€¢ \bullet The right adjoint is less familiar grammatically, but for example, if â€œwaterâ€ is a mass noun, then â€œa body of waterâ€ is a count noun.

this is taken from here:
\url{https://golem.ph.utexas.edu/category/2013/03/spivak_on_category_theory.html}
where it seems that CN and MN are related to Spivak's Oolgs!


