\item
after the HOM construction

It is common that one of the Hom functor's arguments is fixed and the resulting
functors are known as the *(contravaraint and covaraint) yoneda functor(s)*.
What we really mean is that we can `curry' the |Hom| functor, since
it can be shown that |ğ’³ âŸ¶ (ğ’´ ^ ğ’µ) â‰… (ğ’³ Ã— ğ’´ âŸ¶ ğ’µ)| where |^ â‰” Func|, to obtain:
a functor |ğ’ âŸ¶ (ğ’ áµ’áµ–) ^ ğ’®eğ“‰|.

%% I **vaguely** recall a notation is to write the arguments superscript of the fixed argument.
%% That is, |_áµ  â‰” (Id {A} âŸ¶ g)| and |á¶ _ â‰” (f âŸ¶ Id {A})|.
%% This poses some difficulty in Agda, so we use |ğ’´| and |ğ’´Ë˜| for the covaraint and
%% contravaraint versions of Yoneda.


This functor can be shown to be an `embedding' and so known as `the yoneda embedding',
and this informs us that a category is ``represetned'' by set-valued functors.
Thus the study of a category can be delegated to the study of functors.

SEE AUX.LAGDA regarding |yonedalemma|


DISCUSS WHY THE NAME YONEDA.


\item
add in the section on nat.trans. as functor categories.

%%
%% n-transfor(mation)s are functors C x G^n --> D for G^n is the n-category free on the cellular n-globe. Urs Schreiber
%%
%% "Transfor" is due to Sjoerd Crans and is a portmanteau of "transformation" and "functor." One can think of a k-transfor as like a degree-k map of chain complexes: it takes each 0-cell to a k-cell, each 1-cell to a (k+1)-cell, etc. -- this unifies functors with higher transfors. â€“ Mike Shulman

\item
add when discussing limits

{\bf category of cones}
The constant map |K : âˆ€ {X Y} â†’ X â†’ Y â†’ X,  K x y = x| can be made into a functor
|ğ’¦ : ğ’ âŸ¶ ğ’ ^ ğ’Ÿ| by sending an object |C| to ``a constant functor'':
the functor that on objects is
|K C : Obj ğ’ â†’ Obj ğ’Ÿ| and on morphisms is |K (Id {C}) : âˆ€ {x y} â†’ x âŸ¶ y â†’ K x âŸ¶ K y|,
and by sending morphisms |f : A âŸ¶ B| to natural transformations |K f : {C : Obj ğ’} â†’ A âŸ¶ B|.

also can then use this when discussing adjunctions later on

Observe that a natural transformation |Î· : ğ’¦ C âŸ¶ F| boils down to a transformation
|Î· : âˆ€ {X} â†’ C âŸ¶ F X| with triangle-equalities
|f : A âŸ¶ B â‡’  Î· {A} â¨¾ F f = ğ’¦ C f â¨¾ Î· {B} = Î· {B}|.

Now we set
|Cones G â‰” Î£ C âˆ¶ Obj ğ’ â€¢ NatTrans (ğ’¦ C) G|. The objects are `cones to |G| with apex |C|',
and cone morphisms are |ğ’|-maps satisfying certain triangle-equalities:
|(C , Î·) âŸ¶ (C' , Î·') â‰” Î£ Î¸ âˆ¶ C âŸ¶ C' â€¢ âˆ€ x â€¢ Î·â‚“ = Î¸ â¨¾ Î·'â‚“|.

(apparently cannot have nested comment environements)
begin{comment}
\begin{spec}
   (C, Î·) âŸ¶ (C', Î·') in Cones G
=  (C âŸ¶ C' in ğ’) and (Î· âŸ¶ Î·' in (Func ğ’¥ ğ’)^ğŸš )
Now,
  Î· âŸ¶ Î·' in (Func ğ’¥ ğ’)^ğŸš
