\item
A functor from |ğ’| to |ğ’Ÿ| can be thought of as ``a |ğ’Ÿ|-representation of |ğ’|''
---the most obvious case is probably that the linear representation of groups, where
|ğ’| is a group and |ğ’Ÿ| is the category of vector spaces and linear transformations and so
such a functor realizes the group elements and operation as invertible matrices (since group elements are the morphisms in the category as group and so must be mapped to linear transformations which are really just matrices and since functors preserve inverses the matrices must be invertible) and matrix
multiplication (since functors preserve composition and composition of linear transformations is tantamount to matrix multiplication), respectively.
Perhaps move this example down to the section on basis and mention how linear transformations
are matrices due to the notion of basis and then mention this case as another interesting example
of representation. Yeah probably do that!
{\sc perhaps consider discussing representation of, say, posets
as it requires less abstract algebra knowledge. Then perhaps tie that in with yoneda and
so justifying the term `representation'.}

Another example of representation is that of power sets: subsets correspond to predicates, i.e.,
in |ğ’®eğ“‰|, |(X âŸ¶ ğŸš) â‰… â„™ X| where |ğŸš| is a 2-element set.

\item

Notes from reading \url{http://bartoszmilewski.com/2014/09/29/how-to-get-enriched-over-magmas-and-monoids/} ::

\begin{spec}

The defn of a cat can be recast as follows


Category' C:
  Ob : Set                                           -- objects
  Hom   : Ob x Ob â†’ Obj ğ’®eğ“‰                           -- hom-sets
  ğ“‚  : âˆ€ {a b c} â†’ Hom (a , b) Ã— Hom (a , c) â†’ Hom (a,c) -- composition, multiplication
  ğ’¾  : âˆ€ {a} â†’ {â˜…} â†’ Hom (a,a)                         -- unit "elements"
  assoc : â€¦
  rightId : ğ“‚ âˆ˜ (Id Ã— ğ’¾) â‰¡ ğ“‡  where ğ“‡ : âˆ€ {A} â†’ A Ã— {â˜…} â‰… A , i.e. (Ã— {â˜…}) â‰… Id (nat trans)
  leftId  : ğ“‚ âˆ˜ (ğ’¾ Ã— Id) â‰¡ ğ“  where ğ“ : âˆ€ {A} â†’ {â˜…} Ã— A â‰… A , i.e., ({â˜…} Ã— ) â‰… Id

Where all the arrows are functions, i.e., morphisms of ğ’®eğ“‰.

Notice, for left identity,
  âˆ€ {a b} {f : Hom (a,b)} â†’ ğ“‚(ğ’¾ {a} â˜… , f) â‰¡ f
â‡” â€¦ â†’ ğ“‚ âˆ˜ (ğ’¾ {a} Ã— Id { Hom(a,b) }) (â˜… , f) â‰¡ ğ“ (â˜… , f)
â‡” ğ“‚ âˆ˜ (ğ’¾ Ã— Id) â‰¡ ğ“

We want to generlise and so replace (ğ’®eğ“‰, Ã—, {â˜…}) with a category ğ’± and binary endofunctor
âŠ• : ğ’± Ã— ğ’± âŸ¶ ğ’± which has some unit ğŸ™. Now elementhip was encoded by functions |{â˜…} â†’ Y|,
where |{â˜…}| is the unit of |Ã—|, and so we mimic this and encode elementship by |ğ’±|-morphisms
|ğŸ™ âŸ¶ Y| ---notice that we have not claimed |ğŸ™| is terminal.

Then with these replacements, we obtain:

(ğ’± , âŠ•, ğŸ™)-EnrichedCategory C:
  Ob  : Set                                           -- type of objects
  Hom : Ob x Ob â†’ Obj ğ’±                             -- mapping of "hom-objects"
  ğ“‚  : âˆ€ {a b c} â†’ C (a , b) âŠ• C (a , c) âŸ¶ C (a,c) -- multiplication morphisms (in ğ’±)
  ğ’¾  : âˆ€ {a} â†’ ğŸ™ âŸ¶ C (a,a)                          -- unit "elements" (morphisms in ğ’±)
  assoc : â€¦
  rightId : ğ“‚ âˆ˜ (Id Ã— ğ’¾) â‰¡ ğ“‡  where ğ“‡ : âˆ€ {A} â†’ A âŠ• ğŸ™ â‰… A , i.e. (âŠ• ğŸ™) â‰… Id (nat trans)
  leftId  : ğ“‚ âˆ˜ (ğ’¾ Ã— Id) â‰¡ ğ“  where ğ“ : âˆ€ {A} â†’ ğŸ™ âŠ• A â‰… A , i.e., (ğŸ™ âŠ•) â‰… Id

Observe we cannot speak of ``elements'' of |Hom(a,a)| since it is not a set and so we mimic
elements by requesting maps from the terminal object.

Notice, for example, we cannot even form the expression ğŸ™ â†’ Hom(a,a) since ğŸ™ and Hom(a,a) are not
sets and as such there is no function-space between them! Consequently, we are forcefully led to
use the notion of morphism available: that of ğ’± morphisms!

A triple (ğ’±, âŠ•, ğŸ™) with the unit and associtiity laws is known as a "monoidal category".

[ex0]
any monoid, regarded as a category, is a monoidal category.

cats with finite products are monoidal.

[ex1]
Let ğ’Ÿ be the category with object-set â„• and morphisms |m âŸ¶ n| being order-presering
functions |1..m âŸ¶ 1..n|. Then (ğ’Ÿ, +, 0) is a monoidal category.

[ex1']
The ğ’Ÿ of [ex1] is a Poset-enriched category with object-set â„• and hom-objects
|Î» m n â†’ 1..m âŸ¶ 1..n (in Poset)|. (or so I claim!)

[ex2]
For any cat ğ’, Endo(ğ’) â‰” ğ’ ^ ğ’ is a monoidal category with functor composition and the
identity functor. ---recall `a monad is just a monoid in the category of endofunctors'.

A "monoid" "in" (ğ’±, âŠ•, ğŸ™) is a triple (X : Obj ğ’±, m : X âŠ• X âŸ¶ X, e : ğŸ™ âŸ¶ X)
with assotictivity m âˆ˜ (m âŠ• Id) = m âˆ˜ (Id âŠ• m) âˆ˜ assoc
(
   âˆ€ x, y, z â€¢  (x m y) m z = x m (y m z)
â‡” â‹¯ â€¢ m( m (x,y) , z ) = m( x, m(y , z) )
â‡” â‹¯ â€¢ m âˆ˜ (m Ã— Id) ( (x,y) , z) = m âˆ˜ (Id Ã— m) (x, (y, z))
â‡” m âˆ˜ (m Ã— Id) = m âˆ˜ (Id Ã— m) âˆ˜ assoc
)
and unity m âˆ˜ (Id âŠ• e) = ğ“‡
(
    âˆ€ x â€¢ m(x , e) = x
