We call this an "internal algebraic structure" since it's underlying carrier is not an object of
ğ’®eğ“‰.

wait a minute, a "a monoid in a monoidal category" is just "a one-object enriched-category"!
See p171 of catsformaths for examples.

[ex2']
A monoid in (ğ’œğ’·, âŠ•, â„¤) is a ring, and a monoid in k-ğ“œğ“ğ““ is just a k-algebra.

[ex3]
Every cat ğ’ which has (co)products and a (co)terminal category is a monoidal category.

[ex4]
Categories enriched in (ğ’®eğ“‰, Ã—, {â˜…}) are just usual categories.

[ex4]
Let ğ’± be a symmetric monoidal closed category. Define |_* : ğ’±áµ’áµ– âŸ¶ ğ’± : x â†¦ x ^ ğŸ™|
then we have a natural transformation |Id âŸ¶ **|.
(Isn't is the case that |X â‰… X*|, ie |Id â‰… _*|, but unnaturally so since we obtain this via
yoneda/indirect-inequality? See freyd intro to abelian cats book.)

[ex5]
a one-object category is a monoid,
a one-object Ab-category is a ring with unity where Ab is the category of abelian groups; i.e.
one-object groupoids whose composition is commutative.
Now a "left module" over a ring R is an Ab-functor |R âŸ¶ Ab|, for a right-module we use
|R áµ’áµ– âŸ¶ Ab|! So much algebra expressed so succiently :: abstract algebra made easy.
Consider citing dummit and foote!
(is a field a one-object Ab-groupoid ?)


An example enriched category is ``enriching a category over itself''.
If ğ’± has exponentials ---the way to treat morphisms as objects; think of data-vs-methods---
then we can use those as "internal-hom-sets":

Suppose that we have a right adjoint to the `tensor product' |âŠ•|, that is
|(âŠ• X) âŠ£ (^ X)|, i.e., |âˆ€ X, Y, Z â€¢ eval : (Z âŠ• X âŸ¶ Y) â‰… (Z âŸ¶ Y ^ X)| natural in |Z, Y|;
that is, |(Y ^ X, eval)| is the `best' pair |Î£ Z âˆ¶ Obj â€¢ Z âŠ• X âŸ¶ Y|.
That is to say, we can objectify the notion of hom-set.
(Notice that one can go the other way around: a category is `closed' if it has a notion of
internal hom-sets and then a left-adjoint yields a tensor-product!)
Then, we obtain |(X âŸ¶ Y) â‰… (ğŸ™ âŠ• X âŸ¶ Y) â‰… (ğŸ™ âŸ¶ Y ^ X)| which says: the external hom-set is
isomorphic to the elements of the internal hom-set.

Define ğ’±ğ’± to be the categeory enriched over ğ’± as follows:
  Ob  = Obj ğ’±                                         -- type of objects
  Hom X Y = X ^ Y                             -- "internal hom sets"
  ğ“‚  = (use exponential characterisaton and assoc then apply âŠ•)
  ğ’¾  = (use eponential char on identity of ğ’±)
  assoc = ???
  rightId = ??? ;;; ğ“‚ âˆ˜ (Id Ã— ğ’¾) â‰¡ ğ“‡  where ğ“‡ : âˆ€ {A} â†’ A âŠ• ğŸ™ â‰… A , i.e. (âŠ• ğŸ™) â‰… Id (nat trans)
  leftId  = ??? ;;; ğ“‚ âˆ˜ (ğ’¾ Ã— Id) â‰¡ ğ“  where ğ“ : âˆ€ {A} â†’ ğŸ™ âŠ• A â‰… A , i.e., (ğŸ™ âŠ•) â‰… Id
  
Anyhow, the notion of enriched-functor is nearly the same as before,

Functor F (between categories enriched over (ğ’±, âŠ•, ğŸ™) ) :
  Fâ‚€ : Obâ‚ â†’ Obâ‚‚                                -- object mapping
  Fâ‚ : âˆ€ {a b} â†’ Homâ‚(a,b) âŸ¶ Homâ‚‚(Fâ‚€ a, Fâ‚€ b)  -- arrow morphisms (in ğ’±)

Natural transformation from F to G:
  Î· : âˆ€ {x} â†’ ğŸ™ âŸ¶ Homâ‚‚(F x , G X)   -- "component" morphsims
  prf : âˆ€ {a b : Ob} â†’ ğ“‚ âˆ˜ (F âŠ• Î· {b}) âˆ˜ ğ“‡â»Â¹ â‰¡ ğ“‚ âˆ˜ (Î· {a} âŠ• G) âˆ˜ ğ“â»Â¹ -- naturality condition
  -- the composition is category |ğ’±|

Recall that for the (ğ’®eğ“‰, Ã—, {â˜…}) case,
âˆ€ {a b} {f : a âŸ¶ b} â†’
    F f â¨¾ Î· {b} â˜… â‰¡ Î· {a} â˜… â¨¾ G f
â‡”  â‹¯ â†’ ğ“‚ (F f , Î· {b} â˜…) â‰¡ ğ“‚ (Î· {a} â˜… , G f)
â‡”  â‹¯ â†’ ğ“‚ âˆ˜ (F Ã— Î· {b}) (f , â˜…) â‰¡ ğ“‚ âˆ˜ (Î· {a} Ã— G) (â˜… , f)
â‡”  â‹¯ â†’ ğ“‚ âˆ˜ (F Ã— Î· {b}) (ğ“‡â»Â¹ f) â‰¡ ğ“‚ âˆ˜ (Î· {a} Ã— G) (ğ“â»Â¹ f)
â‡” âˆ€ {a b : Ob} â†’ ğ“‚ âˆ˜ (F Ã— Î· {b}) âˆ˜ ğ“‡â»Â¹ â‰¡ ğ“‚ âˆ˜ (Î· {a} Ã— G) âˆ˜ ğ“â»Â¹

This' the so-called ``naturality hexagon'', since there are six |ğ’±|-morphisms involved.

Yoneda let's us construe an arbitrary category in the familar setting of functions and elements
that is |ğ’®eğ“‰|, so we expect enriched-yoneda to give us a |ğ’±|-perspective.

A "representable enriched functor" is a functor |Hom(X,_)| from an enriched category ğ’ to ğ’±ğ’±:
objects |Y| of enriched category ğ’ are `represented' by objects |Hom(X,Y)| of the better understood and structure-rich category |ğ’±|.

The enriched-yoneda says that for any enriched-functor |F| from |ğ’| to |ğ’±ğ’±|,
the enriched-nattrans |Hom(X,_) âŸ¶ F| are in bijection with elements |ğŸ™ âŸ¶ F K|
---these are both sets.
\end{spec}

See G. M. Kelly, Basic Concepts of Enriched Category Theory
\url{http://www.tac.mta.ca/tac/reprints/articles/10/tr10.pdf}

