%}}}

\item
{\bf natural means no reference to types}

The idea that a natural transformation cannot make reference to the type variable at all can be
seen by yet another example.

\begin{spec}
  data ğŸ™ : Set where â˜… : ğŸ™

  -- a choice function: for any type X, it yields an argument of that type
  postulate Îµ : (X : Set) â†’ X

  nay : âˆ€ {X} â†’ X â†’ X
  nay {X} _ = Îµ X
\end{spec}

Now nautrality |Id f â¨¾ nay {B} = nay {A} â¨¾ Id f| breaks as witnessed by
|f = (Î» _ â†’ Îµâ„• + 1) : ğŸ™ â†’ â„•|.
\begin{comment}
\begin{spec}
  Id f â¨¾ nay {â„•}
=
  f â¨¾ (Î» _ â†’ Îµ â„•)
=
  Î» _ â†’ Îµ â„•
â‰ 
  Î» _ â†’ Îµ â„• + 1
=
  Î» _ â†’ f (Îµ ğŸ™)
=
  nay {ğŸ™} â¨¾ Id f
\end{spec}
\end{comment}

From this we may hazard the following:
if we have natural transformations |Î·áµ¢ : âˆ€ {X : Objáµ¢} â†’ F X âŸ¶ G X|
where the |Objáµ¢| partition the objects available ---ie, |Obj = Î£ i â€¢ Objáµ¢|---
then the transformation |Î· {(i, X)} = Î·áµ¢| is generally unnatural since it clearly makes choices,
for each partition.

\item
{\bf natural means uniformaly and simultaneously defined}

A family of morphisms is `natural in x' precisely when it is defined
\emph{simultaneously} for all |x| ---there is no inspection of some particular x here and there,
no it is uniform! With this view, the naturality condition is thought of as a `simultaneity'
condition. \href{https://www.google.ca/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&ion=1&espv=2&ie=UTF-8&client=ubuntu#q=general%20theory%20of%20natural%20equivalences}{[Rephrasing GToNE]}

The idea of naturality as uniformly-definable is pursued by
\href{http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.107.2336&rep=rep1&type=pdf}{Hodges and Shelah}.

\item

{\bf naturality is restructure-modify commutativity}

Recall that a functor can be thought of as endowing an object with structure.
Then a transformation can be thought of as a restructuring operation and naturality means
that it doesn't matter whether we restructure or modify first, as long as we do both.

\item
{\bf natural means obvious}

It may help to think of ``there's a natural transformation from F to G'' to mean
``there's an obvious/standard/canconical way to transform F structure into G structure''.

Likewise, ``F is naturally isomorphic to G'' may be read ``F is obviously isomorphic to G''.

Sometimes we can show ``F X is isomorphic to G X, if we make a choice dependent on X''
and so the isomorphism is not obvious, since a choice must be made.

\item
{\bf naturality is promotion}

I think Richard Bird refers to the naturality condition as a promotion law where the functors
involved are thought of as (list) constructions.

The nomenclature is used 
\href{http://www.cs.ox.ac.uk/files/3390/PRG69.pdf}{``to express the idea than operation on a compund structure can be `promoted' into its componenets'.}

Reading |F f â¨¾ Î· {B} = Î· {A} â¨¾ G f| from left to right:
mapping f over the result of handling a complicated strucure is the same as mapping f over the
complex dataum than handling the result.

Lists give many examples of natural transformations by considering
\href{https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/3-540-51305-1_24}{a categorical approach to the theory of lists}.

\item
{\bf naturality as a rewrite rule}

The naturality condition can be seen as a rewrite rule that let's us replace a complicated or
inefficient side with a simplier or more efficient yet equivalent expression.
I think I first learned this view of equations at the insistence of
\href{https://www.google.ca/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&ion=1&espv=2&ie=UTF-8&client=ubuntu#q=algebra%20of%20programming}{Richard Bird}.


\item

{\bf naturality is just model morphism}

Given two functors |F,G : ğ’ âŸ¶ ğ’Ÿ| let us construe them as only graph homomorphisms.
Then each is a model of the graph |ğ’°â‚€ ğ’| ---each intereprets the nodes and edges of |ğ’°â‚€ ğ’| as
actual objects and morphisms of |ğ’Ÿ|--- and a natrual transformation is then nothing
more than a morphism of models.

{\sc was the notion of model morphisms mentioned earlier when
models were introduced?}


\item
{\bf naturality yields pattern matching}

In the setting of types and functions, |Î· : F âŸ¶Ì‡ G| means we have |Î· (F f x) = G f (Î· x)|
which when read left-to-right says that |Î·| is defined by pattern-matching on its argument
to obtain something of the form |F f x| then it is defined recursively by examining |x| and then
applying |G f| to the result ---of course there's some base case |f| definitions as well.

Alternatively, the input to |Î·| is of the form |F â€¦| and its
output is of the form |G â€¦|.

\end{enumerate}

%}}}
   %{{{ Example nat trans.
\subsection*{Example nat trans}

\begin{enumerate}

\item
{\bf pointwise monotonicity}

A functor among poset categories is an order-preserving function and a natural transformation
|f âŸ¶ g| is a proof that |f â‰¤ g| pointwise: |âˆ€ x â€¢ f x â‰¤ g x| ---all the other pieces for a natural
transformation are automatic from the definition of poset category.

\item
{\bf conjugation}

A functor among monoids (as categories) is just a monoid homomorphism:
\[|(M, âŠ•, e) âŸ¶ (N, âŠ—, d) â‰” Î£ h âˆ¶ M â†’ N â€¢ âˆ€ x,y â€¢ h(x âŠ• y) = h x âŠ— h y âˆ§ h e = d|\]
A natural transformation |(f, prf) âŸ¶ (g, prf')| is a point |n : N| with
|âˆ€ x âˆ¶ M â€¢ f x âŠ— n = n âŠ— g x|, a `conjugation' by |n| that takes |f| to |g|.
\begin{comment}
  Î· âˆˆ (f , prf) âŸ¶ (g , prf')
=                               { defn of natural transformation }
  Î· âˆˆ âˆ€ {x} â†’ f x âŸ¶ g x in M
  with âˆ€ m â€¢ f m â¨¾ Î· = Î· â¨¾ g m
=                               { arrows in monoid categories }
  Î· âˆˆ N with âˆ€ x âˆ¶ M â€¢ f x â¨¾ Î· = Î· â¨¾ g x
=                               { composition in monoid categories }
  Î· âˆˆ N with âˆ€ x âˆ¶ M â€¢ f x âŠ— Î· = Î· âŠ— g x
\end{comment}  
  
\item
{\bf fold}

Recall from the introduction |ğ’°(S, âŠ•, e) = S| was the underlying functor from monoids to sets.
Let |ğ’° Ã— ğ’°| be the functor that for objects |M â†¦ ğ’° M Ã— ğ’° M| and for morphisms
|h â†¦ Î» (x,y) â†’ (h x, h y)|. Then the monoid multiplication (of each monoid) is a natural
transformation |ğ’° Ã— ğ’° âŸ¶ ğ’°|, where naturality says that for any monoid homomorphism |h|, the
application of |ğ’° h| to the (monoid) multiplication of two elements is the same as the
(monoid) multiplication of the |ğ’° h|-images of the two elements, and this is evident from the
homomorphism condition.

Extending to finite products, |ğ’± â‰” Î£ n âˆ¶ â„• â€¢ âˆ i âˆ¶ 1..n â€¢ ğ’°|, the natural transformation
|ğ’± âŸ¶Ì‡ ğ’°| is usually called fold, reduce, or cata and
|ğ’±| is known as the
free monoid functor with notations |A* = List A = ğ’± A|.

Loosely put,
\begin{spec}

ğ’±â‚€ : Monoid â†’ Set
ğ’±â‚€ M = Î£ n âˆ¶ â„• â€¢ âˆ i : 1..n â€¢ ğ’° M -- finite sequences of elements from M

ğ’±â‚ : âˆ€ {M N : Monoid} â†’ (M âŸ¶ N) â†’ ğ’±â‚€ M â†’ ğ’±â‚€ N
ğ’±â‚ (h , prf) = Î» (n , xâ‚, â€¦, xâ‚™) â†’ (n , h xâ‚ , â€¦ , h xâ‚™)

fold : âˆ€ {M : Monoid} â†’ ğ’±â‚€ M â†’ ğ’°â‚€ M
fold {(M, âŠ•, e)} = Î» (n , xâ‚, â€¦, xâ‚™) â†’ xâ‚ âŠ• â‹¯ âŠ• xâ‚™
\end{spec}

Now for any monoid homomorphism |h|, applying induction, yields
\begin{spec}
hâ‚€(xâ‚ âŠ• â‹¯ âŠ• xâ‚™) = hâ‚€ xâ‚ âŠ• â‹¯ âŠ• hâ‚€ xâ‚™ where hâ‚€ = ğ’° (hâ‚€, prf) = ğ’° h
\end{spec}
which is just naturality
\begin{spec}
ğ’° h âˆ˜ fold {M} = fold {N} âˆ˜ ğ’± h
\end{spec}

\item
{\bf every operation in any multisorted algebraic structure gives a natural
transformation. 
}

This is mentioned in the Barr-wells-ctcs category theory text, citing
[Linton,1969b], [Linton, 1969a].

For example, |src, tgt| ---from the graph signature--- give natural transformations
|V âŸ¶ E| from the vertex functor to the edge functor |â€¦|

\item
{\bf representability}

Recall that |V(G)| is essentially |â„™â‚€ âŸ¶ G| where
|â„™â‚™| is the graph of |n| edges on |n+1| vertices |0..n| with typing |i : i-1 âŸ¶ i|,
which I like to call `the path graph of length n'; and in particular |â„™â‚€| is the the graph of
just one dot, called 0, and no edges. ---earlier I used the notation [n], but I'm using P since
I like the view point of paths.

What does it mean that `|V(G)| is essentially |â„™â‚€ âŸ¶ G|'?
It means that the vertices functor
---|ğ’± : Graph âŸ¶ Set| takes objects |G â†¦ V(G)| and morphisms |h â†¦ ver h|---
can be represented as the hom functor |(â„™â‚€ âŸ¶_)|, that is to say
|ğ’± â‰… (â„™â‚€ âŸ¶ _) within Func Graph Set| ---notice that we arrived at this expression by
quote-unqoute eta-reducing `|V(G)| is essentially |â„™â‚€ âŸ¶ G|' ;)

More generally, we have the functor |â„™â‚™ âŸ¶ _| which yields all paths of length n for a given
graph.

Observe that we also have an edges functor.
\\
Recall the `untyped edges', or arrows, |A(G) â‰” Î£ x âˆ¶ V(G) â€¢ Î£ y âˆ¶ V(G) â€¢ (x âŸ¶ y)|,
then (arrows) |ğ’œ : Graph âŸ¶ Set| takes objects |G â†¦ A(G)| and morphisms
|h â†¦ Î» (x,y,e) â†’ (ver h x, ver h y, edge h e)|.

\end{enumerate}
%}}}

%{{{ Func
* {Functor Categories}

With a notion of morphisms between functors, one is led inexorably to ask
whether functors as objects and natural transformations as morphisms constitute
a category?
They do!
However, we leave their definition to the reader ---as usual, if the reader is ever so desperate
for solutions, they can be found as comments in the unruliness that is the source file.
\begin{spec}
  Func : âˆ€ {i j i' j'} (ğ’ : Category {i} {j}) (ğ’Ÿ : Category {i'} {j'}) â†’ Category
  Func ğ’ ğ’Ÿ = {! exercise !}
\end{spec}

A hint: the identity natural transformation is the obvious way to get from |F X| to |F X|,
for any |X| given |F| ---well the only way to do so, without assuming anything else about the
functor |F|, is simply |Id {F X}|. This is the `natural' choice, any other choice would be
`unnatural' as it would require some `cleverness'. Another hint: the obvious way to define
|Î· â¨¾ Î³| to get |F X âŸ¶ H X| from |F X âŸ¶ G X âŸ¶ H X| is composition of morphisms in the category!
That is, pointwise composition. Nothing `clever', just using the obvious candidates!

\begin{comment}
\begin{code}
 instance
  Func : âˆ€ {i j i' j'} (ğ’ : Category {i} {j}) (ğ’Ÿ : Category {i'} {j'}) â†’ Category {â„“suc (i âŠ j âŠ i' âŠ j')} {j' âŠ i âŠ j}
  Func {i} {j} {i'} {j'} ğ’ ğ’Ÿ = record {
      Obj = Functor ğ’ ğ’Ÿ
    ; _âŸ¶_ = NatTrans
    ; _â¨¾_ = Î» {A B C} Î· Î³ â†’ comp {A} {B} {C} Î· Î³
    ; assoc = Î» {F G H K Î· Î³ Ï‰} â†’ nattransext {i} {j} {i'} {j'} {ğ’} {ğ’Ÿ} {F} {K} (comp {F} {H} {K} (comp {F} {G} {H} Î· Î³) Ï‰) (comp {F} {G} {K} Î· (comp {G} {H} {K} Î³ Ï‰)) assoc
    ; Id = Î» {F} â†’ iden F
    ; leftId = Î» {F G Î·} â†’ nattransext {i} {j} {i'} {j'} {ğ’} {ğ’Ÿ} {F} {G} (comp {F} {F} {G} (iden F) Î·) Î· leftId
    ; rightId = Î» {F G Î·} â†’ nattransext {i} {j} {i'} {j'} {ğ’} {ğ’Ÿ} {F} {G} (comp {F} {G} {G} Î· (iden G)) Î· rightId
    }
    where
      iden : (A : Functor ğ’ ğ’Ÿ) â†’ NatTrans A A
      iden A = Id , (rightId âŸ¨â‰¡â‰¡âŸ© â‰¡-sym leftId)

      comp : {A B C : Functor ğ’ ğ’Ÿ} â†’ NatTrans A B â†’ NatTrans B C â†’ NatTrans A C
      comp = Î» {F G H} Î·pf Î³pf â†’ let (Î· , nat) = Î·pf ; (Î³ , nat') = Î³pf in
           (Î» {X} â†’ Î· {X} â¨¾ Î³ {X}) , (Î» {A B f} â†’ begin
           mor F f â¨¾ Î· {B} â¨¾ Î³ {B}
          â‰¡âŸ¨ â‰¡-sym assoc âŸ¨â‰¡â‰¡âŸ© (â‰¡-congâ‚‚ _â¨¾_ nat â‰¡-refl âŸ¨â‰¡â‰¡âŸ© assoc) âŸ©
            Î· {A} â¨¾ mor G f â¨¾ Î³ {B}
          â‰¡âŸ¨ â‰¡-congâ‚‚ _â¨¾_ â‰¡-refl nat' âŸ¨â‰¡â‰¡âŸ© â‰¡-sym assoc âŸ©
            (Î· {A} â¨¾ Î³ {A}) â¨¾ mor H f
          âˆ)
\end{code}
\end{comment}
This is a good exercise as it will show you that there is an identity functor and that composition of functors
is again a functor. Consequently, functors are in abundance: given any two, we can form new ones by composition.

It is a common construction that when a type |Y| is endowed with some structure, then we can endow
the function space |X â†’ Y|, where |X| is any type, with the same structure and we do so
`pointwise'. This idea is formalized by functor categories.
Alternatively, one can say we have `categorified' the idea; where
\emph{categorification} is the process of replacing types and functions with categories and
functors and possibly adding some coherence laws.

There are people who adhere to something called `set theory' which is essentialy type theory but
ignoring types, loosely put they work only with the datatype
\begin{spec}
data SET : Set where
  Elem : âˆ€ {A : Set} â†’ A â†’ SET
\end{spec}
Such heathens delegate types-of-types into `classes' of `small' and `big' sets and it's not
uniform enough for me.
Anyhow, such people would say that functor categories ``cannot be constructed (as sets)'' unless
one of the categories involved is ``small''. Such shenanigans is ignored due to the hierarchy of
types we are using :-)

We must admit that at times the usage of a single type, a `uni-typed theory' if you will can be
used when one wants to relise types in an extrinsic fashion rather than think of data as
intrinsically typed. Everything has its place ... nonetheless, I prefer (multi)typed settings!

%}}}
   %{{{ examples of functor categories

\subsection*{examples of functor categories}

\begin{enumerate}

\item
Let |ğŸ™ â‰” [ â€¢ ]| be the discrete category of one object (and only the identity arrow on it).
Then |ğ’ â‰… Func ğŸ™ ğ’|.

\item
For example,
let |ğŸšâ‚€ â‰” [â€¢ â€¢]| be the discrete category of two objects.
Then square category can be defined |ğ’ âŠ— ğ’ âˆ¶â‰… Func ğŸšâ‚€ ğ’|.
The subscript 0 is commonly used for matters associated with objects and
the name |ğŸšâ‚€| is suggestive of the category of 2 objects only.

More generally, if |ğ’©| is the discrete category of |n| objects, then
the |n|-fold product category is defined
|(âˆ i âˆ¶ 1..n â€¢ ğ’) âˆ¶â‰… Func ğ’© ğ’|.

\item
We can add an arrow to |ğŸšâ‚€| to obtain another category...

Let |ğŸš â‰” â€¢ âŸ¶ â€¢| be the category of two objects, call them 0 and 1, with one arrow between them.
Then a functor |ğŸš âŸ¶ ğ’| is precisely a morphism of |ğ’| and a natural transformation
|f âŸ¶ g| boils down to just a pair of morphisms |(h,k)| with |h â¨¾ g = f â¨¾ k|.
Hence, `the arrow category of |ğ’|' is
$\mathcal{C}^{\mathbb{2}} := \mathcal{C}^{\to}
$|â‰” Func ğŸš ğ’|:
the category with objects being |ğ’|-morphisms and morphisms being `commutative squares'.

Notice that the notation $\mathcal{C}^{\mathbb{2}}$ is an abbreviation for |Func ğŸš ğ’| and
as such it is common to write |ğ’³ ^ ğ’´ â‰” Func ğ’³ ğ’´|.

\item
It is a common heuristic that when one suspects the \emph{possibility} of a category |ğ’|, then one
can make probes to discover its structure. The objects are just functors |ğŸ™ âŸ¶ ğ’| and the
morphisms are just functors |ğŸš âŸ¶ ğ’|.

\item

The ``category of presheaves of |ğ’|'' is the category |PSh ğ’ â‰” Func (ğ’ áµ’áµ–) ğ’®eğ“‰|.

This is a pretty awesome category since it allows nearly all constructions in |ğ’®eğ“‰| to be
realised! Such as subsets, truth values, and even powersets! All these extra goodies make it
a ``topos'' aka ``power allegory'' ---the first is a category that has all finite limits and
a notion of powerset while the second, besides the power part, looks like a totally different beast;
the exhilaration!

\item

The `slice category' of |ğ’| `over' |B : Obj ğ’| is the category
|ğ’ / B â‰” Î£ F âˆ¶ Func ğŸš ğ’ â€¢ (F 1 = B)|. That is, the category of objects being |ğ’|-morphisms with
target |B| and morphisms |f âŸ¶ g| being |(h,k)| with |h â¨¾ g = f â¨¾ k| but a natural choice for
|k : B âŸ¶ B| is |Id| and so we can use morphism type |(f âŸ¶' g) â‰” Î£ h : src f âŸ¶ src g â€¢ h â¨¾ g = f|.
This is seen by the observation |(h, k) âˆˆ f âŸ¶ g â‡” h âˆˆ (f â¨¾ k) âŸ¶' g|; of course a formal
justification is obtained by showing |_âŸ¶_ â‰… _âŸ¶'_ within Func (ğ’ áµ’áµ– âŠ— ğ’) ğ’®eğ“‰|...which I have
not done and so may be spouting gibberish!

\begin{comment}
The isomorphism is witnessed as follows.

To :: |(h,k) : f âŸ¶ g â‡’ h : (f â¨¾ k) âŸ¶' g|,

from :: |h : f âŸ¶' g â‡’ (h, Id) : f âŸ¶ g|.

Rid ::
\begin{spec}
    (h , k) : f âŸ¶ g
â‡’  h : f â¨¾ k âŸ¶' g
â‡’ (h, Id) : f â¨¾ k âŸ¶ g
â‰¡ (h , k) : f âŸ¶ g
\end{spec}
where the equivalence is just
|(h,k) âˆˆ f âŸ¶ g â‡” (h , Id) âˆˆ (f â¨¾ k) âŸ¶ g|.

Lid ::
\begin{spec}
   h : f âŸ¶' g
â‡’ (h, Id) : f âŸ¶ g
â‡’ h : f â¨¾ Id âŸ¶' g
â‰¡ h : f âŸ¶' g
\end{spec}

Of course none of this is formal(ly in Agda) and so should be taken with great precaution!
---since it may be all wrong!
\end{comment}

Just as the type |Î£ x âˆ¶ X â€¢ P x| can be included in the type |X|, by forgetting the second
component, so too the category |Î£ F âˆ¶ ğŸš âŸ¶ ğ’ â€¢ F 1 â‰ˆ B| can be included into the category
|ğ’| and we say it is a `subcategory' of |ğ’|.

The notation |Î£ o âˆ¶ Obj ğ’ â€¢ P o| defines the subcategory of |ğ’| obtained by deleting
all objects not satisfying |P| and deleting all morphisms incident to such objects; i.e.,
the category |ğ’Ÿ| with
\[|Obj ğ’Ÿ â‰¡ Î£ o âˆ¶ Obj ğ’ â€¢ P o|    \text{ and }   |(o , pf) âŸ¶ğ’Ÿ (o' , pf') â‰¡ o âŸ¶ğ’ o'| \]

This is the largest/best/universal subcategory of |ğ’| whose objects satisfy |P|.
\\
Formalize this via a universal property ;)

\item
{\bf Coslices of |ğ’®eğ“‰| are functor categories}

%% [fibres]
|Func S ğ’®eğ“‰ â‰… ğ’®eğ“‰ / S|, where S in the left is construed as a discrete category and in the right
is construed as an object of |ğ’®eğ“‰|.

This is because a functor from a discrete category need only be a function of objects since
there are no non-identity morphisms. Then a functor |f : S âŸ¶ Set| yields an |S|-targeted
function |(Î£ s âˆ¶ S â€¢ f s) â†’ S : (Î» (s , X) â†’ s)|. Conversely a function |g : X â†’ S| yields
a functor |S âŸ¶ Set : (Î» s â†’ (Î£ x âˆ¶ X â€¢ g x â‰¡ s))|.

\begin{comment}
[to]
Indeed a functor |f : S âŸ¶ Set| is determined by giving a set |f s| for each element |s âˆˆ S|
---since there are no non-identity morphisms. But this is preceiscely a function |g| with target
|S|! Define |g : (Î£ s â€¢ f s) â†’ S| that given an element (s,x) returns s.

[from]
Conversley,
given a function |g : X â†’ S| we have a functor |S âŸ¶ SET| determined by sending each element s
to its preimage under g: |gâ»Â¹{s} â‰” Î£ x â€¢ g x â‰ˆ s|, an object of SET.

Rid:
\begin{spec}
given f : S âŸ¶ Set

  from (to f)
= Î» s â†’ Î£ x âˆˆ src(to f) â€¢ (to f) x â‰ˆ s
= Î» s â†’ Î£ s' âˆˆ S â€¢ Î£ x' âˆˆ f s' â€¢ (to f) (s', x') â‰ˆ s
= Î» s â†’ Î£ s' âˆˆ S â€¢ Î£ x' âˆˆ f s' â€¢ s' â‰ˆ s
â‰¡âŸ¨ one point rule âŸ©
  Î» s â†’ Î£ x' âˆˆ f s â€¢ âŠ¤   where âŠ¤ short for âŠ¤rue
= Î» s â†’ f s              top is unit for products
