\end{spec}
some of those equlaities are clearly not equalities!
---maybe simplified if we get rid of those |âˆˆ| and rephrase to use the word `type' rather than
`set'!

then the other inverse law...
\end{comment}

Because of this example, |ğ’ / B| can be thought of as `|ğ’|-objects indexed by |B|'.

\item
{\bf Natural transformations as functor categories}

In a similar spirit, we can identify natural transformations as functors!
\[|Func ğ’ (ğ’Ÿ ^ ğŸš) â‰… (Î£ F , G âˆ¶ ğ’ âŸ¶ ğ’Ÿ â€¢ NatTrans F G)|\]

A functor |N : ğ’ âŸ¶ ğ’Ÿ ^ ğŸš| gives, for each object |C : Obj ğ’| an object in |ğ’Ÿ ^ ğŸš| which
is precisely an arrow in |ğ’Ÿ|, type it as |N C : FC âŸ¶ GC| i.e., |FC = N C 0 , GC = N C 1|,
and for each arrow |f : A âŸ¶ B in ğ’| we obtain an arrow |N f : N A âŸ¶ N B| in |ğ’Ÿ ^ ğŸš|
which is precisely a commutative square in |ğ’Ÿ|,
that is a pair of |ğ’Ÿ|-arrows |(Ff , Gf) = Nf| with |N A â¨¾ Gf = Ff â¨¾ N B|.

Extended the notation |Fx| of the previous paragraph to a functor |ğ’ âŸ¶ ğ’Ÿ| by |F x â‰” Fx|; likewise for |G|.
The object and morphism mappings are clear, but what about functoriality? We prove it for both |F, G| together.
\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{spec}
Identity:

  (F Id , G Id)
â‰¡âŸ¨ definition of F and G âŸ©
  N Id
â‰¡âŸ¨ N is a functor âŸ©
  Id in ğ’Ÿ ^ ğŸš
â‰¡âŸ¨ identity in arrow categories âŸ©
  (Id , Id)
\end{spec}
\columnbreak
\begin{spec}
Composition:

  ( F (f â¨¾ g) , G (f â¨¾ g) )
â‰¡âŸ¨ definition of F and G âŸ©
  N (f â¨¾ g)
â‰¡âŸ¨ N is a functor âŸ©
  N f â¨¾ N g
â‰¡âŸ¨ definition of F and G âŸ©
  (Ff, Gf) â¨¾ (Fg , Gg)
â‰¡âŸ¨ composition in arrow categories âŸ©
  (Ff â¨¾ Fg , Gf â¨¾ Gg)
â‰¡âŸ¨ definition of F and G as notation âŸ©
  (F f â¨¾ F g , G f â¨¾ G g)
\end{spec}
\end{multicols}

Sweet!

Conversely, given a natural transformation |Î· : F âŸ¶ G|
we define a functor |N : ğ’ âŸ¶ ğ’Ÿ ^ ğŸš| by sending objects |C| to |Î· {C} : F C âŸ¶ G C|, which is an
object is |ğ’Ÿ ^ ğŸš|, and sending morphisms |f : A âŸ¶ B| to pairs |(G f , F f)|, which is a morphism
in |ğ’Ÿ ^ ğŸš| due to naturality of |Î·|: |Î· {A} â¨¾ G f = F f â¨¾ Î· {B}|. It remains to show that |N|
preserves identities and composition.

Now it remains to show that these two processes are inverses and the isomorphism claim is complete. Woah!

Similarly, we can show |Func (ğŸš âŠ— ğ’) ğ’Ÿ â‰… (Î£ Fâ‚€ , Fâ‚ âˆ¶ ğ’ âŸ¶ ğ’Ÿ â€¢ NatTrans Fâ‚ Fâ‚‚)| by showing
the ``the universal property of exponentiation'' |ğ’³ âŸ¶ (ğ’µ ^ ğ’´) â‰… (ğ’³ âŠ— ğ’´ âŸ¶ ğ’µ|, or more
directly: to/from direction obtained by setting |H i = Fáµ¢| on objects and likewise for morphisms
but with |H(Id, 1) = Î·| where |1 : 0 âŸ¶ 1| is the non-identity arrow of |ğŸš|.

(Spoilers! Alternatively: |Arr (Func ğ’ ğ’Ÿ) â‰… ğŸš âŸ¶ ğ’ ^ ğ’Ÿ â‰… ğ’ Ã— ğŸš âŸ¶ ğ’Ÿ| since |ğ’ğ’¶ğ“‰| has exponentials,
and so the objects are isomorphic; i.e., natural transformations correspond to functors |ğ’Ã—ğŸšâŸ¶ğ’Ÿ|)

Why are we mentioning this alternative statement? Trivia knowledge of-course!
On a less relevant note, if you're familiar with the theory of stretching-without-tearing,
formally known as topology and it's pretty awesome, then you might've heard of paths and
deformations of paths are known as homotopies and are just continuous functions
|X Ã— I âŸ¶ Y| for topological spaces |X| and |Y| and |I = [0,1]| is the unit interval.
Letting |ğ’¥ = ğŸš| be the `categorical interval' we have that functors |ğ’ Ã— ğ’¥ âŸ¶ ğ’Ÿ|
are, by the trivia-relevant result, the same as natural transformations.
That is, natural transformations extend the notion of homotopies, or path-deformations.

\item
On \href{http://mathoverflow.net/a/75686/42716}{mathoverflow}, the above is recast succinctly as:
a natural transformation from |F| to |G| is a functor, targeting an arrow category, whose `source'
is |F| and whose `target' is |G|.
\[
  |
    (F âŸ¶Ì‡ G : ğ’ âŸ¶ ğ’Ÿ) â‰… Î£ Î· âˆ¶ ğ’ âŸ¶ Arr ğ’Ÿ â€¢ Src âˆ˜ Î· = F âˆ§ Tgt âˆ˜ Î· = G
  |
\]
Where, the projection functors
\begin{spec}
Src, Tgt                         : Arr ğ’Ÿ âŸ¶ ğ’Ÿ
Src (Aâ‚ , Aâ‚‚ , f)                = Aâ‚
Src (f  , g  , hâ‚ , hâ‚‚ , proofs) = hâ‚
\end{spec}
with |Tgt| returning the other indexed items.

\end{enumerate}
%}}}
   %{{{ Graphs as functors
\subsection*{Graphs as functors}

We give an example of a functor by building on our graphs from before.
After showing that graphs correspond to certain functors, we then
mention that the notion of graph-map is nothing more than the the associated
natural transformations!

\begin{code}
 module graphs-as-functors where
\end{code}

Let us construct our formal graph category, which contains the ingredients for
a graph and a category and nothing more than the equations needed of a category.
The main ingredients of a two-sorted graph are two sort-symbols |E, V|, along with
two function-symbols |s, t| from |E| to |V| ---this is also called `the signature
of graphs'. To make this into a category, we need function-symbols |id| and a composition
for which it is a unit.
\begin{code}
  -- formal objects
  data ğ’¢â‚€ : Set where E V : ğ’¢â‚€

  -- formal arrows
  data ğ’¢â‚ : ğ’¢â‚€ â†’ ğ’¢â‚€ â†’ Set where
     s t : ğ’¢â‚ E V              
     id  : âˆ€ {o} â†’ ğ’¢â‚ o o 

  -- (forward) composition
  fcmp : âˆ€ {a b c} â†’ ğ’¢â‚ a b â†’ ğ’¢â‚ b c â†’ ğ’¢â‚ a c
  fcmp f id = f
  fcmp id f = f
\end{code}

   %{{{ ğ’¢ : Category
Putting it all together,
\begin{code}
  instance
   ğ’¢ : Category
   ğ’¢ = record
        { Obj = ğ’¢â‚€
        ; _âŸ¶_ = ğ’¢â‚
        ; _â¨¾_ = fcmp
        ; assoc = Î» {a b c d f g h} â†’ fcmp-assoc f g h
        ; Id = id
        ; leftId = left-id
        ; rightId = right-id
        }
    where
       -- exercises: prove associativity, left and right unit laws
\end{code}
\begin{comment}
\begin{code}
       -- proofs are just C-c C-a after some casing
       fcmp-assoc : âˆ€ {a b c d} (f : ğ’¢â‚ a b) (g : ğ’¢â‚ b c) (h : ğ’¢â‚ c d) â†’ fcmp (fcmp f g) h â‰¡ fcmp f (fcmp g h)
       fcmp-assoc s id id = â‰¡-refl
       fcmp-assoc t id id = â‰¡-refl
       fcmp-assoc id s id = â‰¡-refl
       fcmp-assoc id t id = â‰¡-refl
       fcmp-assoc id id s = â‰¡-refl
       fcmp-assoc id id t = â‰¡-refl
       fcmp-assoc id id id = â‰¡-refl
       right-id : âˆ€ {a b} {f : ğ’¢â‚ a b} â†’ fcmp f id â‰¡ f
       right-id {f = s} = â‰¡-refl
       right-id {f = t} = â‰¡-refl
       right-id {f = id} = â‰¡-refl
       left-id : âˆ€ {a b} {f : ğ’¢â‚ a b} â†’ fcmp id f â‰¡ f
       left-id {f = s} = â‰¡-refl
       left-id {f = t} = â‰¡-refl
       left-id {f = id} = â‰¡-refl
\end{code}
\end{comment}
%}}}

   %{{{ toFunc : Graph â†’ Functor ğ’¢ ğ’®eğ“‰
Now we can show that every graph |G| gives rise to a functor: a semantics of |ğ’¢| in |ğ’®eğ“‰|.
\begin{code}
  toFunc : Graph â†’ Functor ğ’¢ ğ’®eğ“‰
  toFunc G = record { obj = âŸ¦_âŸ§â‚€ ; mor = âŸ¦_âŸ§â‚ ; id = â‰¡-refl ; comp = Î» {x y z f g} â†’ fcmp-â¨¾ {x} {y} {z} {f} {g} }
    where
      âŸ¦_âŸ§â‚€ : Obj ğ’¢ â†’ Obj ğ’®eğ“‰
      âŸ¦ ğ’¢â‚€.V âŸ§â‚€ = Graph.V G
      âŸ¦ ğ’¢â‚€.E âŸ§â‚€ = Î£ x âˆ¶ Graph.V G â€¢ Î£ y âˆ¶ Graph.V G â€¢ Graph._âŸ¶_ G x y
          
      âŸ¦_âŸ§â‚ : âˆ€ {x y : Obj ğ’¢} â†’ x âŸ¶ y â†’ âŸ¦ x âŸ§â‚€ âŸ¶ âŸ¦ y âŸ§â‚€
      âŸ¦ s âŸ§â‚ (src , tgt , edg) = src
      âŸ¦ t âŸ§â‚ (src , tgt , edg) = tgt
      âŸ¦ id âŸ§â‚ x = x

      -- exercise: |fcmp| is realised as functional composition
      fcmp-â¨¾ : âˆ€{x y z} {f : ğ’¢â‚ x y} {g : ğ’¢â‚ y z} â†’ âŸ¦ fcmp f g âŸ§â‚ â‰¡ âŸ¦ f âŸ§â‚ â¨¾ âŸ¦ g âŸ§â‚
\end{code}
\begin{comment}
\begin{code}
      fcmp-â¨¾ {f = s} {id} = â‰¡-refl
      fcmp-â¨¾ {f = t} {id} = â‰¡-refl
      fcmp-â¨¾ {f = id} {s} = â‰¡-refl
      fcmp-â¨¾ {f = id} {t} = â‰¡-refl
      fcmp-â¨¾ {f = id} {id} = â‰¡-refl
\end{code}
\end{comment}
%}}}

Conversely, every such functor gives a graph:
\begin{code}
  fromFunc : Functor ğ’¢ ğ’®eğ“‰ â†’ Graph
  fromFunc F = record {
      V    = obj F ğ’¢â‚€.V
    ; _âŸ¶_ = Î» x y â†’ Î£ e âˆ¶ obj F ğ’¢â‚€.E â€¢ src e â‰¡ x Ã— tgt e â‰¡ y -- the type of edges whose source is x and target is y
    }
    where tgt src : obj F ğ’¢â‚€.E â†’ obj F ğ’¢â‚€.V
          src = mor F ğ’¢â‚.s
          tgt = mor F ğ’¢â‚.t
\end{code}

It is to be noted that we can define ``graphs over |ğ’|'' to be the category |Func ğ’¢ ğ’|.
Some consequences are as follows: notion of graph in any category, the notion of graph-map
is the specialisation of natural transformation (!), and most importantly: all the power of functor categories
is avaiable for the study of graphs.

In some circles, you may hear people saying an `algebra over the signature of graphs' is an interpretation
domain (|ğ’|) and an operation (|Functor ğ’¢ ğ’|) interpreting the symbols.

We no longer make use of this two-sorted approach to graphs.
%}}}

%{{{ A few categorical constructions :: _âŠ—_, _áµ’áµ–, Hom, pointwise, Fst, Snd
* {A few categorical constructions}

We briefly take a pause to look at the theory of category theory.
In particular, we show a pair of constructions to get new categories from old ones,
interpret these constructions from the view of previously mentioned categories, and
discuss how to define the morphism type |_âŸ¶_| on morphisms themselves, thereby
yielding a functor.

%{{{ Opposite
\subsection{Opposite}
The `dual' or `opposite' category |ğ’ áµ’áµ–| is the category constructed from |ğ’| by
reversing arrows: |(A âŸ¶ B) â‰” (B âŸ¶ A)| and then necessairly |(f â¨¾ g) â‰” g â¨¾ f|.
A contravariant functor, or cofunctor, is a functor F from an opposite category and so
there is a reversal of compostions: |F(f â¨¾ g) = F g â¨¾ F f|.
\begin{spec}
 _áµ’áµ– : âˆ€ {i j} â†’ Category {i} {j} â†’ Category
 ğ’ áµ’áµ– = {! exercise !}
\end{spec}
\begin{comment}
\begin{code} 
 _áµ’áµ– : âˆ€ {i j} â†’ Category {i} {j} â†’ Category
 ğ’ áµ’áµ– = record {
      Obj = Obj ğ’
    ; _âŸ¶_ = Î» A B â†’ (B âŸ¶ A)
    ; _â¨¾_ = Î» f g â†’ (g â¨¾ f)
    ; assoc = â‰¡-sym assoc
    ; Id = Id
    ; leftId = rightId
    ; rightId = leftId
    }
\end{code}
\end{comment}

Notice that |ğ’ áµ’áµ– áµ’áµ– = ğ’| and |ğ’ áµ’áµ– â‰… ğ’|
--one may have an intuitive idea of what this isomorphsim means,
but formally it is only meaningful in the context of an ambient category; keep reading ;)

-- we must admit that for categories, the notion of isomorphism is considered less useful
than that of equivalence which weakens the condition of the to-from functors being
inverses to just being naturaly isomorphic to identites. See evil.

Some interpretations:
\begin{itemize}
\item
  |ğ’®eğ“‰ áµ’áµ–| is usual sets and functions but with `backwards composition':
\begin{code}
 infix 10 _âˆ˜_
 _âˆ˜_ : âˆ€ {i j } {{r : Category {i} {j}}} {A B C : Obj r} â†’ B âŸ¶ C â†’  A âŸ¶ B â†’ A âŸ¶ C
 f âˆ˜ g = g â¨¾ f
 \end{code}
 Indeed, we have  |g â¨¾ f within ğ’ = f âˆ˜ g within ğ’ áµ’áµ–|; which is how these composition operators
 are usually related in informal mathematics (without mention of the ambient categories of-course).

On a more serious note, the opposite of ğ’®eğ“‰ is clearly |ğ“‰eğ’®| haha
---technically for the purposes of this pun we identify the words `opposite' and `reverse'.

\item
  For a discrete category, its opposite is itself.
\item
  For a monoid (viewed as a category), its opposite is itself if the monoid operation is commutative, otherwise
  it is the `dual monoid'.
\item
  For a poset (viewed as a category), its opposite is the `dual poset': |(P, âŠ‘)áµ’áµ– = (P, âŠ’)|.

  In particular, the `least upper bound', or `supremum' in |(P, âŠ‘)| of two elements
  |x,y| is an element |s| with the `universal property': |âˆ€ z â€¢ x âŠ‘ z âˆ§ y âŠ‘ z â‰¡ s âŠ‘ z|.
  However, switching |âŠ‘| with |âŠ’| gives us the notion of `infimum', `greatest upper bound'!
  So any theorems about supremums automatically hold for infimums since the infifum is nothing
  more than the supremum in the dual category of the poset.

  It is not difficult to see that this idea of `2 for the price of 1' for theorems holds for all
  categories.

\item
  What about the category of functors and natural transformations?
\end{itemize}

Speaking of functors, we can change the type of a functor by |áµ’áµ–|-ing its source and target,
while leaving it alone,
\begin{code}
 -- this only changes type
 opify : âˆ€ {i j i' j'} {ğ’ : Category {i} {j}} {ğ’Ÿ : Category {i'} {j'}} â†’ Functor ğ’ ğ’Ÿ â†’ Functor (ğ’ áµ’áµ–) (ğ’Ÿ áµ’áµ–)
 opify F = record { obj = obj F ; mor = mor F ; id = Functor.id F ; comp = Functor.comp F }
\end{code}

\begin{quote}
``Category Theory is the |opi|um of the people!'' --- Karl Marx might say it had cats existed in his time
\end{quote}

This two definitions seem to indicate that we have some form of opposite-functor |â€¦| ;)
---keep reading!

|opify| seems to show that |Functor ğ’ ğ’Ÿ â‰¡ Functor (ğ’ áµ’áµ–) (ğ’Ÿ áµ’áµ–)|, or alternatively a
functor can have `two different types' ---this is akin to using the integers as reals
without writing out the inclusion formally, leaving it implicit; however, in the Agda mechanization
everything must be made explicit ---the type system doesn't let you get away with such things.
Professor Maarten Fokkinga has informed me that
the formalization allowing multiple-types is called a
\href{http://maartenfokkinga.github.io/utwente/mmf92b.pdf}{pre-category}.
%}}}
  %{{{ âˆ‚ and ah-yeah
\subsubsection*{ah-yeah: âˆ‚ and dagger categories}

With |ğ’ğ’¶ğ“‰| in-hand, we can formalise the opposite, or |âˆ‚|ual, functor:
\begin{code}
 âˆ‚ : âˆ€ {i j} â†’ ğ’ğ’¶ğ“‰ {i} {j} âŸ¶ ğ’ğ’¶ğ“‰
 âˆ‚ = record { obj = _áµ’áµ– ; mor = opify ; id = â‰¡-refl ; comp = â‰¡-refl }
\end{code}

Conjecture: assuming categories are equipped with a contravariant invultionary functor that is identity on objects, we can show that the identity functor is naturally isomorphic to the opposite functor.

\begin{code}
 ah-yeah : âˆ€ {i j}
     -- identity on objects cofunctor
     â†’ (_Ë˜  : {{ğ’ : Obj (ğ’ğ’¶ğ“‰ {i} {j})}} â†’ âˆ€ {x y : Obj ğ’} â†’ x âŸ¶ y â†’ y âŸ¶ x)
     â†’ (IdË˜ : âˆ€ {ğ’} {x : Obj ğ’} â†’ (Category.Id ğ’ {x}) Ë˜ â‰¡ Category.Id ğ’ {x})
     â†’ (â¨¾-Ë˜ : âˆ€ {ğ’} {x y z : Obj ğ’} {f : x âŸ¶ y} {g : y âŸ¶ z} â†’ (f â¨¾ g)Ë˜ â‰¡ g Ë˜ â¨¾ f Ë˜)
     -- which is involutionary
     â†’ (Ë˜Ë˜ : âˆ€ {ğ’} {x y : Obj ğ’} {f : x âŸ¶ y} â†’ (f Ë˜) Ë˜ â‰¡ f)
     -- which is respected by other functors
     â†’ (respect : âˆ€ {ğ’ ğ’Ÿ} {F : ğ’ âŸ¶ ğ’Ÿ} {x y : Obj ğ’} {f : x âŸ¶ y} â†’ mor F (f Ë˜) â‰¡ (mor F f)Ë˜)
     -- then
     â†’ âˆ‚ â‰… Id within Func (ğ’ğ’¶ğ“‰) ğ’ğ’¶ğ“‰
\end{code}
\begin{spec}
 ah-yeah = {! exercise !}
\end{spec}
\begin{comment}
\begin{code}
 ah-yeah {i} {j} _Ë˜ IdË˜ â¨¾-Ë˜ Ë˜Ë˜ respect = record {
     to = II
   ; from = JJ
   ; lid = nattransext {ğ’ = ğ’ğ’¶ğ“‰} {ğ’ğ’¶ğ“‰} {F = âˆ‚} {G = âˆ‚} (Category._â¨¾_ ğ’©ğ“‰ {âˆ‚} {Id} {âˆ‚} II JJ) (Category.Id ğ’©ğ“‰ {âˆ‚}) (funcext â‰¡-refl (â‰¡-sym Ë˜Ë˜))
   ; rid = nattransext {ğ’ = ğ’ğ’¶ğ“‰} {ğ’ğ’¶ğ“‰} {F = Id} {G = Id} (Category._â¨¾_ ğ’©ğ“‰ {Id} {âˆ‚} {Id} JJ II) (Category.Id ğ’©ğ“‰ {Id}) (funcext â‰¡-refl (â‰¡-sym Ë˜Ë˜)) }
           -- we use NatTrans extensionality on category |ğ’ğ’¶ğ“‰| on functor |Id| with natural transformations
           -- the LHS starting at Id going to |âˆ‚| then to |Id| and the RHS being the natural transformation on the identity functor.
   where
     ğ’©ğ“‰ = Func ğ’ğ’¶ğ“‰ ğ’ğ’¶ğ“‰ -- the category of |ğ’©|atural transormations as morphisms
     
     I : âˆ€ {ğ’} â†’ obj âˆ‚ ğ’ âŸ¶ ğ’
     I = Î» {ğ’} â†’ record { obj = Id ; mor = _Ë˜ ; id = IdË˜ ; comp = â¨¾-Ë˜ }
     
     Inat : âˆ€ {ğ’ ğ’Ÿ} {F : ğ’ âŸ¶ ğ’Ÿ} â†’ mor âˆ‚ F â¨¾ I â‰¡ I â¨¾ F
     Inat = Î» {ğ’ ğ’Ÿ F} â†’ funcext {F = mor âˆ‚ F â¨¾ I} {G = I â¨¾ F}â‰¡-refl (Î» {x y f} â†’ respect {ğ’} {ğ’Ÿ} {F} {y} {x} {f})

     II : NatTrans âˆ‚ Id
     II = I , (Î» {ğ’} {ğ’Ÿ} {F} â†’ Inat {ğ’} {ğ’Ÿ} {F})

     J : âˆ€ {ğ’} â†’ ğ’ âŸ¶ obj âˆ‚ ğ’
     J = record { obj = Id ; mor = _Ë˜ ; id = IdË˜ ; comp = â¨¾-Ë˜ }

     Jnat : âˆ€ {ğ’ ğ’Ÿ} {F : ğ’ âŸ¶ ğ’Ÿ} â†’ J â¨¾ mor âˆ‚ F â‰¡ F â¨¾ J
     Jnat = Î» {ğ’ ğ’Ÿ F} â†’ funcext {F = J â¨¾ mor âˆ‚ F} {G = F â¨¾ J} â‰¡-refl (Î» {x y f} â†’ â‰¡-sym (respect {ğ’} {ğ’Ÿ} {F} {x} {y} {f}))

     JJ : NatTrans Id âˆ‚
     JJ = J , (Î» {ğ’} {ğ’Ÿ} {F} â†’ â‰¡-sym (Jnat {ğ’} {ğ’Ÿ} {F}))
\end{code}
\end{comment}

Some things to note.
\begin{itemize}
\item
Categories whose morphisms are all isomorphisms are called `groupoids' ---groups are just one-object groupoids.
Consequently, restricted to groupoids the opposite functor is naturally isomorphic to the identity functor!

In fact, the group case was the motivator for me to conjecture the theorem, which took a while to prove since I hadn't
a clue what I needed to assume. Here we'd use |a Ë˜ â‰” a â»Â¹|.

\item
Consider the category |Rel| whose objects are sets and whose morphisms are `typed-relations' |(S, R, T)|, where |R| is a relation
from set |S| to set |T|, and
composition is just relational composition
---the notion of `untyped', or multi-typed, morphisms is formalized as pre-categories;
see \href{http://maartenfokkinga.github.io/utwente/mmf92b.pdf}{Fokkinga}.
Then we can define an endofunctor by taking |-Ë˜| to be relational converse: |x (R Ë˜) y â‡” y R x|.
Consequently, restricted to the category |Rel| we have that the opposite functor is naturally isomorphic to the identity functor.

\begin{comment}
Indeed, in the proof above, all quantification's become over a unit type: only possibility is
|Rel|.

Then, |I : Rel áµ’áµ– âŸ¶ Rel| and |J : Rel âŸ¶ Rel áµ’áµ–|, and the lid-rid proofs amount to saying that
the two are inverses.
\end{comment}
\end{itemize}
%
The above items are instance of a more general concept, of course.

A category with an involutionary contravariant endofunctor that is the identity on objects
is known as \emph{a dagger category, an involutive/star category, or a category with converse}
---and the functor is denoted as a superscript suffix by |â€ , *, Ë˜|, respectively.
The dagger notation probably comes from
the hilbert space setting while the converse notation comes from the relation algebra setting.
As far as I know, the first two names are more widely known.
A dagger category bridges the gap between arbitrary categories and groupoids.

Just as matrices with matrix multiplication do not form a monoid but rather a category, we have
that not all matrices are invertible but they all admit transposition and so we have a dagger
category. In the same vein, relations admit converse and so give rise to a category with converse.

Besides relations and groupoids, other examples include
\begin{itemize}
\item
discrete categories with the dagger being the identity functor
\item
every monoid with an anti-involution is trivially a dagger category; e.g.,
lists with involution being reverse.

\item
commutative monoids are anti-involutive monoids with antiinvolution being identity
\end{itemize}

Spoilers!! Just as the category of categories is carestian closed, so too is the category of dagger
categories and dagger preserving functors (cf |respect| above).

%% a pseudoheap is a set H with an binary-operation assining function  âŸ¨_âŸ© : H â†’ (H Ã— H â†’ H)
%% such that
%% mutual-assoc:  (a âŸ¨bâŸ© c) âŸ¨dâŸ© e = a âŸ¨bâŸ© (c âŸ¨dâŸ© e)
%% commutative: x âŸ¨aâŸ© y = y âŸ¨aâŸ© x
%%
%% Every involutive monoid is a pseudoheap:
%% x âŸ¨yâŸ© z â‰” x Â· y Ë˜ Â· z




%}}}

%{{{ Products
\subsection{Products}

For any two categories |ğ’| and |ğ’Ÿ| we can construct their `product' category
|ğ’ âŠ— ğ’Ÿ| whose objects and morphisms are pairs with components from |ğ’| and |ğ’Ÿ|:
|Obj (ğ’ âŠ— ğ’Ÿ) = Obj ğ’ Ã— Obj ğ’Ÿ| and |(A , X) âŸ¶ (B , Y) = (A âŸ¶ B) Ã— (X âŸ¶ Y)|.
\begin{spec}
 -- we cannot overload symbols in Agda and so using |âŠ—| in-place of more common |Ã—|.
 _âŠ—_ : âˆ€ {i j i' j'} â†’ Category {i} {j} â†’ Category {i'} {j'} â†’ Category
 ğ’ âŠ— ğ’Ÿ = {! exercise !}
\end{spec}
\begin{comment}
\begin{code}
 infix 5 _âŠ—_
 _âŠ—_ : âˆ€ {i j i' j'} â†’ Category {i} {j} â†’ Category {i'} {j'} â†’ Category
 ğ’ âŠ— ğ’Ÿ = record {
      Obj = Obj ğ’ Ã— Obj ğ’Ÿ
    ; _âŸ¶_ = Î» AX BY â†’ let (A , X) = AX ; (B , Y) = BY in (A âŸ¶ B) Ã— (X âŸ¶ Y)
    ; _â¨¾_ = Î» fk gl â†’ let (f , k) = fk ; (g , l) = gl in (f â¨¾ g , k â¨¾ l)
    ; assoc = helper assoc assoc 
    ; Id = Id , Id
    ; leftId = helper leftId leftId
    ; rightId = helper rightId rightId
    }
    where helper : âˆ€ {i j} {A : Set i} {B : Set j} {a a' : A} {b b' : B} â†’ a â‰¡ a' â†’ b â‰¡ b' â†’ (a , b) â‰¡ (a' , b')
          helper â‰¡-refl â‰¡-refl = â‰¡-refl
\end{code}
\end{comment}

Observe that in weaker languages a category is specified by its objects, morphisms, and composition
---the proof obligations are delegated to comments, if they are realized at all.
In such settings, one would need to prove that this construction actually reduces a full-fledged
category. Even worse, this proof may be a distance away in some documentation.
With dependent types, our proof obligation is nothing more than another component of the program,
a piece of the category type.

In a similar fashion we can show that the sum of two categories is again a category and in general
we have the same for quantified variants: |ğ’¬ ğ’ âˆ¶ Family â€¢ ğ’| where |ğ’¬ âˆˆ { âˆ , Î£ }|.
For the empty family, the empty sum yields the category |ğŸ˜| with no objects and
the empty sum yields the category |ğŸ™| of one object.
One can then show the usual `laws of arithmetic' ---i.e., an commutative monoid---
hold in this setting: letting |â˜… âˆˆ {+,Ã—}|, we have
associtivity |A â˜… (B â˜… C) â‰… (A â˜… B) â˜… C|, symmetry |A â˜… B â‰… B â˜… A|,
unit |ğŸ™ Ã— A â‰… ğŸ˜ + A â‰… A|, and zero |ğŸ˜ Ã— A â‰… ğŸ˜|.
These notions can be defined for any category though the objects may or may not exist
--- in |ğ’®eğ“‰| and |ğ’¢ğ“‡ğ’¶ğ“…ğ’½|, for example, they do exist ;) ---and these associated arithmetical
laws also hold.

Question: what of the distributively law,
|A Ã— (B + C) â‰… (A Ã— B) + (A Ã— C)|, does it hold in the mentioned cases?
Let |ğ’«ğ’®eğ“‰| be the category of sets with a distinguished point, i.e.,  |Î£ S : Obj ğ’®eğ“‰ â€¢ S|, and
functions that preserve the `point', one can then show ---if he or she so desires, and is not
lazy--- that this category has notions of product and sum but distributively fails.

Some interpretations:
\begin{itemize}
\item
  For discrete categories, this is the usual Cartesian product.
\item
  For monoid (or poset) categories, this says that the product of two monoids (or posets) is again
  a monoid (respectively poset. This follows since the product does not affect the number of
  objects and so the product is again a one-object category, i.e., a monoid (poset respectively).
\end{itemize}

As expected, we have projections,
\begin{code}
 Fst : âˆ€ {i j i' j'} {ğ’ : Category {i} {j}} {ğ’Ÿ : Category {i'} {j'}} â†’ Functor (ğ’ âŠ— ğ’Ÿ) ğ’
 Fst = record { obj = projâ‚ ; mor = projâ‚ ; id = â‰¡-refl ; comp = â‰¡-refl }

 Snd : âˆ€ {i j i' j'} {ğ’ : Category {i} {j}} {ğ’Ÿ : Category {i'} {j'}} â†’ Functor (ğ’ âŠ— ğ’Ÿ) ğ’Ÿ
 Snd = record { obj = projâ‚‚ ; mor = projâ‚‚ ; id = â‰¡-refl ; comp = â‰¡-refl }
\end{code}

%}}}
  %{{{ currying
\subsubsection*{Currying}

