\end{code}

An example bifunctor is obtained by extending the --> to morphisms:
given |f : A âŸ¶ B , g : C âŸ¶ D| we define |(f âŸ¶ g) : (B âŸ¶ C) â†’ (A âŸ¶ C)| by
|Î» h â†’ f â¨¾ h â¨¾ g| as this is the only way to define it so as to meet the type requirements.
\begin{code}
 Hom : âˆ€ {i j} {ğ’ : Category {i} {j} } â†’ Functor (ğ’ áµ’áµ– âŠ— ğ’) ğ’®eğ“‰
   -- hence contravariant in `first arg' and covaraint in `second arg'
