\part{solving the initial goal}

%{{{ Path definition
* {Path definition}
We can now define a `path' of length |n| of a graph |G| to be a graph-map
|[ n ] âŸ¶ G|.
\begin{code}
Pathâ‚€ : â„• â†’ Graphâ‚€ â†’ Set (â„“suc â„“â‚€)
Pathâ‚€ n G = [ n ]â‚€ ğ’¢âŸ¶â‚€ G
\end{code}
Unfolding the definition of graph-morphisms, this just says that a path of length |n|
BACKEND-ERROR %% consists of a sequence |âŸ¨v_0, v_1, v_2,  â€¦, v_nâŸ©| of vertices of |G| and a sequence of edges of
BACKEND-ERROR %% |G| |âŸ¨e_0, e_1, â€¦, e_n-1âŸ©| with typing |e_i : v_i âŸ¶ v_(i+1)|.

The definition is pretty slick! However, as the name suggests, perhaps we can concatenate paths
and it's not at all clear how to do this for the vertex- and edge- morphisms of the graph-maps
involved, whereas it's immediately clear how to do this with sequences: we just concatenate the
sequences and ensure the result is coherent.

Since the vertices can be obtained from the edges via |src| and |tgt|, we can dispense with them
and use the definition as outlined above by
\begin{code}
open import Data.Vec using (Vec ; lookup)

record Pathâ‚ (n : â„•) (G : Graphâ‚€) : Set (â„“suc â„“â‚€) where
  open Graphâ‚€
  field
    edges     : Vec (E G) (suc n)
    coherency : {i : Fin n} â†’ tgt G (lookup (` i) edges) â‰¡ src G (lookup (fsuc i) edges)
\end{code}
That is, edges BACKEND-ERROR %% |[e_0, â€¦, e_n]| with coherency |tgt e_i â‰¡ src e_i+1|.

Great, we've cut the definition of |Pathâ‚€| in half but that fact that we get a raw list of edges
and then need coherency to ensure that it is a well-formed path is still not terribly lovely.
After all, we're in Agda, we're among kings, we should be able to form the list in such a way that
the end result is a path. Let's do that!

Enough of this repetition, let us fix a graph |G|,
\begin{code}
module Path-definition-2 (G : Graphâ‚€) where
  open Graphâ‚€ G

  mutual
    data Pathâ‚‚ : Set where
      _!   : V â†’ Pathâ‚‚
      cons : (v : V) (e : E) (ps : Pathâ‚‚) (s : v â‰¡ src e) (t : tgt e â‰¡ headâ‚‚ ps) â†’ Pathâ‚‚

    headâ‚‚ : Pathâ‚‚ â†’ V
    headâ‚‚ (v !) = v
    headâ‚‚ (cons v e p s t) = v
\end{code}

Defining paths for the parallel-pair approach to graphs leaves us with the need to carry
proofs around, and this is a tad too clunky in this case.

\begin{code}
module Path-definition-3 (G : Graph) where

  open Graph G

  -- handy dandy syntax
  infixr 5 cons
  syntax cons v ps e = v âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ ps -- v goes, by e, onto path ps

  -- we want well-formed paths
  mutual
    data Pathâ‚ƒ : Set where
      _!   : (v : V) â†’ Pathâ‚ƒ
      cons : (v : V) (ps : Pathâ‚ƒ) (e : v âŸ¶ headâ‚ƒ ps) â†’ Pathâ‚ƒ

    headâ‚ƒ : Pathâ‚ƒ â†’ V
    headâ‚ƒ (v !) = v
    headâ‚ƒ (v âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ ps) = v

  -- motivation for the syntax declaration above
  example : (vâ‚ vâ‚‚ vâ‚ƒ : V) (eâ‚ : vâ‚ âŸ¶ vâ‚‚) (eâ‚‚ : vâ‚‚ âŸ¶ vâ‚ƒ) â†’ Pathâ‚ƒ
  example vâ‚ vâ‚‚ vâ‚ƒ eâ‚ eâ‚‚ = vâ‚ âŸ¶[ eâ‚ ]âŸ¶ vâ‚‚ âŸ¶[ eâ‚‚ ]âŸ¶ vâ‚ƒ !

  endâ‚ƒ : Pathâ‚ƒ â†’ V
  endâ‚ƒ (v !) = v
  endâ‚ƒ (v âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ ps) = endâ‚ƒ ps

  -- typed paths
  record _â‡_ (x y : V) : Set where -- |\ squigarrowright|
    field
      path   : Pathâ‚ƒ
      start  : headâ‚ƒ path â‰¡ x
      finish : endâ‚ƒ path  â‰¡ y
\end{code}
This seems great, but there's always room for improvement:

- since the |cons| constructors third argument depends on its first, we must
  use a syntax declaration to get the desired look. Such atheistic is not only
  pleasing but reminiscent of diagrammatic paths;
  moreover, it's guaranteed to be an actual path and not just an
  alternating lists of vertices and edges.
  Using the clunky |Pathâ‚‚|, we'd write
  \begin{spec}
  vâ‚ âŸ¶[ vâ‚â‰ˆseâ‚ , eâ‚ , teâ‚â‰ˆvâ‚‚ ]âŸ¶ vâ‚‚ âŸ¶[ vâ‚‚â‰ˆseâ‚‚ , eâ‚‚ , teâ‚‚â‰ˆvâ‚ƒ ]âŸ¶ vâ‚ƒ !
  where
  syntax cons v e ps s t = v âŸ¶[ s , e , t ]âŸ¶ ps
  \end{spec}
  yuck!

  Finally, the syntax-declaration does not make the emacs agda-mode auto-case using
  the syntax, and so I have to write it out by hand, each time I want to use the syntax.

- Again since |cons| third argument depends on the second argument, we need a mutual
  definition to extract the item of the dependence. Perhaps if we embed this item at
  the type level we may avoid the need of an auxiliary mutually-defined function.

- By defining what the start and finish of a path, we can assign types to it.
  However, this approach is reminiscent of the parallel-pair approach to graphs,
  as in |Graphâ‚€|, which we argued is less preferable to the typed-approach to graphs.
  Perhaps defining paths with types by default, we can reap the benefits and simplicity
  of the typed-approach to graphs.
\begin{code}
module TypedPaths (G : Graph) where

  open Graph G hiding(V)
  open Graph   using (V)

  data _â‡_ : V G â†’ V G â†’ Set where
    _!         : âˆ€ x â†’ x â‡ x
    _âŸ¶[_]âŸ¶_  : âˆ€ x {y Ï‰} (e : x âŸ¶ y) (ps : y â‡ Ï‰) â†’ x â‡ Ï‰
\end{code}

---

Show that graphmaps preserve paths: |(f : G âŸ¶ H)  â†’ x â‡ y â†’ fáµ¥ x â‡ fáµ¥ y|;
this is nothing more than type-preservation for f to be a functor |ğ’«G âŸ¶ ğ’«H| ;)

\begin{spec}
a connected b â‰¡ (a â‡ b) âŠ (b â‡ a) -- path between a and b; not `from a to b'.
\end{spec}
this is an equivalence relation whose equivelnce classes are called the connected components.
Call this collection |ğ’¦G|. For any category |ğ’|, define |ğ’¦ ğ’ â‰” ğ’¦ (ğ’°â‚€ ğ’)| which is a
subcategory of |ğ’|. Phrase the connected components subcategory using a universal property,
thereby avoiding the need for quotient types.

Since graphmaps preserve paths, every graph map can be extended to connected components,
|ğ’¦f : ğ’¦G âŸ¶ ğ’¦H : (connected componenet of x) â†¦ (connected comopnent of fáµ¥ x)|.

Hence, we have a functor |ğ’¦ : Graph âŸ¶ Set|.

Then there is a natural transformation |ğ’± âŸ¶ ğ’¦|, where V is the vertices functor.

Proof.

Such a transformation means we can realise vertices as connected components and this suggests
taking |Î²G : ğ’±G â†’ ğ’¦G| which takes a vertix to the connected-component |Î²|lock that contains it.
Then given graph map |f : G âŸ¶ H|,
\begin{spec}
  ğ’± f â¨¾ Î²G
â‰¡ Î» a â†’ the block containing fáµ¥ a
â‰¡ Î» a â†’ ğ’¦f (the block containg a)
â‰¡ Î²H â¨¾ ğ’¦f
\end{spec}
yeah!


Moreover, if we let |ğ’Ÿ : Set â†’ Cat| be the free category functor that associates each set with
the discrete category over it, then we have |ğ’¦| is the assoicated forgetful functor.

Proof.

given a set map |f : S âŸ¶ ğ’¦ C|, this assigns a connected component for each s of S.
Let |R c| be a choice of Representative for an equivalence block, then
f can be made iinto a functor by sending each s, now construed as an object, to the |C|-object
|R (f s)|.

given a functor |F : ğ’Ÿ S âŸ¶ C|, define a set-map that sends each s to the connected component
that contains it, ie |Î²|.

now verify the needed laws.

I saw this someplace on stack exchange for the adjoint to the free category functor.
Anyhow, should consider the intution(?) behind this construction since it's not immediately clear
why the connected components, that or cuz is nearly 6 in the morning and i am needs of sleep.

src :: \url{http://math.stackexchange.com/questions/1640298/coforgetful-functors}

---

One might think that since we can write
\begin{code}
  src : {x y : V G} (e : x âŸ¶ y) â†’ V G
  src {x} {y} e = x
\end{code}
we can again ignore vertices and it suffices to just keep a coherent list of edges.
Then what is an empty path at a vertex? This' enough to keep vertices around
---moreover, the ensuing terms look like diagrammatic paths! Cool!

One more thing, a handy-dandy combinator for forming certain equality proofs of paths.
\begin{code}
  âŸ¶-â‰¡ : âˆ€{x y Ï‰} {e : x âŸ¶ y} {ps qs : y â‡ Ï‰} â†’ ps â‰¡ qs â†’ (x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ ps) â‰¡ (x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ qs)
  âŸ¶-â‰¡ {x} {y} {Ï‰} {e} {ps} {qs} eq = â‰¡-cong (Î» r â†’ x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ r) eq
\end{code}
Less usefully, we leave as excercises
\begin{spec}
  edges : âˆ€ {x Ï‰} (p : x â‡ Ï‰) â†’ List (Î£ s âˆ¶ V G â€¢ Î£ t âˆ¶ V G â€¢ s âŸ¶ t)
  edges = {! exercise !}

  path-eq : âˆ€ {x y} {p q : x â‡ y} â†’ edges p â‰¡ edges q â†’ p â‰¡ q
  path-eq = {! exercise !}
\end{spec}
Given time, |path-eq| could be rewritten so as to be more easily applicable.
For now, two path equality proofs occur in the document and both are realised by
quick-and-easy induction.
\begin{comment}
Solutions.
\begin{code}
  open import Data.List using (List ; [] ; _âˆ·_)
  edges : âˆ€ {x Ï‰} (p : x â‡ Ï‰) â†’ List (Î£ s âˆ¶ V G â€¢ Î£ t âˆ¶ V G â€¢ s âŸ¶ t)
  edges {x} (.x !) = []
  edges {x} (.x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ ps) = (x , _ , e) âˆ· edges ps

  path-eq : âˆ€ {x y} {p q : x â‡ y} â†’ edges p â‰¡ edges q â†’ p â‰¡ q
  path-eq {x} {p = .x !} {q = .x !} pf = â‰¡-refl
  path-eq {x} {p = .x !} {q = .x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ q} ()
  path-eq {x} {p = .x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ p} {q = .x !} ()
  path-eq {x} {p = .x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ p} {q = .x âŸ¶[ eâ‚ ]âŸ¶ q} pf with edges p | pf
  path-eq {x} {p = .x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ p} {q = .x âŸ¶[ .e ]âŸ¶ q} pf | .(edges q) | â‰¡-refl = âŸ¶-â‰¡ (path-eq (uncons pf))
    where uncons : âˆ€{A : Set} {x y : A} {xs ys : List A} â†’ x âˆ· xs â‰¡ y âˆ· ys â†’ xs â‰¡ ys
          uncons {A} {x} {.x} {xs} {.xs} â‰¡-refl = â‰¡-refl        
\end{code}
\end{comment}
%}}}
%{{{ category of paths over a graph
\subsection{category of paths over a graph}
   %{{{ concatenation ++
Now we turn back to the problem of concatenating two paths.
\begin{code}
  infixr 5 _++_
  _++_ : âˆ€{x y z} â†’ x â‡ y â†’ y â‡ z â†’ x â‡ z
  x ! ++ q = q                                     -- left unit
  (x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ p) ++ q = x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ (p ++ q)        -- mutual-associativity
\end{code}
Notice that the the base case indicate that |!| forms a left-unit for |++|,
while the inductive case says that path-formation associates with path concatenation.

If we had not typed our paths, as in |Pathâ‚‚|, we would need to carry around a
proof that paths are compatible for concatenation:
\begin{spec}
  concatenate : (p q : Path) (coh : end p â‰¡ head q) â†’ Path
  syntax concatenate p q compatibility = p ++[ compatibility ] q
\end{spec}
Even worse, to show |p ++[ c ] q â‰¡ p ++[ c' ] q| we need to invoke proof-irrelevance of
identity proofs to obtain |c â‰¡ c'|, each time we want such an equality! Moving the proof
obligation to the type level removes this need.

As can be seen, being type-less is a terrible ordeal.

%}}}
   %{{{ units of ++[]
Just as the first clause of CONCAT AND BANG %|_++_| indicates |_!| is a left unit,
\begin{code}
  leftId : âˆ€ {x y} {p : x â‡ y} â†’ x ! ++ p â‰¡ p
  leftId = â‰¡-refl
\end{code}
Is it also a right identity?
\begin{code}
  rightId : âˆ€ {x y} {p : x â‡ y} â†’ p ++ y ! â‰¡ p
  rightId {x} {.x} {.x !} = â‰¡-refl
  rightId {x} {y } {.x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ ps} = â‰¡-cong (Î» q â†’ x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ q) rightId
\end{code}

%}}}
   %{{{ ++-assoc
Is this operation associative?
\begin{code}
  assoc : âˆ€{x y z Ï‰} {p : x â‡ y} {q : y â‡ z} {r : z â‡ Ï‰} â†’ (p ++ q) ++ r â‰¡ p ++ (q ++ r)
  assoc {x} {p = .x !} = â‰¡-refl
  assoc {x} {p = .x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ ps} {q} {r} = â‰¡-cong (Î» s â†’ x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ s) (assoc {p = ps})
\end{code}
%}}}

Hence, we've shown that the paths over a graph constitute a category! Let's call it |ğ’« G|.

%}}}
%{{{ |ğ’«|-functor
\subsection{The |ğ’«|ath to freedom}
In the last section, we showed that the paths over a graph make a category,
\begin{code}
ğ’«â‚€ : Graph â†’ Category
ğ’«â‚€ G = let open TypedPaths G in
    record
      { Obj = Graph.V G
      ; _âŸ¶_ = _â‡_
      ; _â¨¾_ = _++_
      ; assoc = Î» {x y z Ï‰ p q r} â†’ assoc {p = p}
      ; Id = Î» {x} â†’ x !
      ; leftId = leftId
      ; rightId = rightId
      }
\end{code}

Can we make |ğ’«| into a functor by definining on morphisms?
That is, to lift graph-maps to category-maps, i.e., functors.

\begin{code}
ğ’«â‚ : âˆ€{G H} â†’ GraphMap G H â†’ Functor (ğ’«â‚€ G) (ğ’«â‚€ H)
ğ’«â‚ {G} {H} f = record { obj = ver f ; mor = mo ; id = â‰¡-refl ; comp = Î» {x} {y} {z} {p} â†’ comp {p = p} }
    where
      open TypedPaths {{...}} public

      mo : {x y : Graph.V G} â†’  x â‡ y â†’ (ver f x) â‡ (ver f y)
      mo (x !) = ver f x !
      mo (x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ p) = ver f x âŸ¶[ edge f e ]âŸ¶ mo p

      comp : {x y z : Graph.V G} {p : x â‡ y} {q : y â‡ z} â†’ mo (p ++ q) â‰¡ mo p ++ mo q
      comp {x} {p = .x !} = â‰¡-refl -- since ! is left unit of ++
      comp {x} {p = .x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ ps} = âŸ¶-â‰¡ (comp {p = ps})
\end{code}
Sweet!

With these two together, we have that |ğ’«| is a functor.

\begin{code}
ğ’« : Functor ğ’¢ğ“‡ğ’¶ğ“…ğ’½ ğ’ğ’¶ğ“‰
ğ’« = record { obj = ğ’«â‚€ ; mor = ğ’«â‚ ; id = Î» {G} â†’ funcext â‰¡-refl (idm {G}) ; comp = funcext â‰¡-refl compmor }
    where
      open TypedPaths {{...}} public
         
      idm : âˆ€ {G} {x y} {p : x â‡ y} â†’ mor (Category.Id ğ’ğ’¶ğ“‰ {ğ’«â‚€ G}) p â‰¡ mor (ğ’«â‚ (Category.Id ğ’¢ğ“‡ğ’¶ğ“…ğ’½)) p
      idm {G} {x} {p = .x !} = â‰¡-refl
      idm {G} {x} {p = .x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ ps} = âŸ¶-â‰¡ (idm {p = ps})

      open Category {{...}}
      compmor : âˆ€ {G H K} {f : G âŸ¶ H} {g : H âŸ¶ K} {x y} {p : x â‡ y} â†’ mor (ğ’«â‚ f â¨¾ ğ’«â‚ g) p â‰¡ mor(ğ’«â‚ (f â¨¾ g)) p
      compmor {x = x} {p = .x !} = â‰¡-refl
      compmor {x = x} {p = .x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ ps} = âŸ¶-â‰¡ (compmor {p = ps})

\end{code}
%}}}

%{{{ freedom
* { Free at last }

|âŸ¦|
``Free at last, free at last, thank God almighty we are free at last.'' -- Martin Luther King Jr.
%% Martin Luther King Jr., I Have a Dream: Writings and Speeches That Changed the World
|âŸ§|

Recall why lists give the `free monoid': we can embed a type |A| into |List A| by the map BACKEND-ERROR %% |[_]|,
and we can lift any map |f : A âŸ¶ B| to a monoid map
BACKEND-ERROR %% |foldr (Î» a b â†’ f a âŠ• b) e : (List A , _++_ , []) âŸ¶ (B, _âŠ•_ , e)|
---i.e., |[aâ‚, â€¦, aâ‚–] â†¦ f aâ‚ âŠ• â‹¯ âŠ• f aâ‚–|---
such that |âˆ€ a â€¢ f a â‰¡ foldr f e [ a ] | and this lifted map is unique.

Likewise, let us show that |ğ’«G| is the `free category' over the graph |G|.
This amounts to saying that there is a way, say graph-map |Î¹|, to embed |G| into |ğ’«G|,
and a way to lift any graph-map |f : G ğ’¢âŸ¶ ğ’°â‚€ ğ’| to a functor |lift f : Functor ğ’«G ğ’|
such that |f â‰¡ Î¹ â¨¾ ğ’°â‚ (lift f)| and uniquely so.

Let's begin!
\begin{code}
module freedom (G : Obj ğ’¢ğ“‡ğ’¶ğ“…ğ’½) {ğ’ : Category {â„“â‚€} {â„“â‚€} } where

  open TypedPaths G using (_! ; _âŸ¶[_]âŸ¶_ ;  _â‡_ ; _++_)
  open Category {{...}}
\end{code}

   %{{{ Defining the needed operations
\subsection{Defining the needed operations}
The only obvious, and most natural, way to embed a graph into its `graph of paths' is to send
vertices to vertices and edges to paths of length 1.
\begin{code}  
  Î¹ : G âŸ¶ ğ’°â‚€ (ğ’«â‚€ G)
  Î¹ = record { ver = Id ; edge = Î» {x} {y} e â†’ x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ y ! }
\end{code}

Given a graph map |f|, following the list-analagoue of |[aâ‚, â€¦, aâ‚–] â†¦ f aâ‚ âŠ• â‹¯ âŠ• f aâ‚–|
we attempt to lift the map onto paths by taking edges |eâ‚, â€¦, eâ‚–| to a morphism |eâ‚' â¨¾ â‹¯ â¨¾ eâ‚–'|
where |eáµ¢' = edge f eáµ¢|.
Of course, we then need to verify that this construction is indeed
functorial.
\begin{code}
  lift : G âŸ¶ ğ’°â‚€ ğ’ â†’ ğ’«â‚€ G âŸ¶ ğ’
  lift f = record {
      obj = Î» v â†’ ver f v -- this is the only way to obtain an object of |ğ’|; hope it works!
     ; mor = toMap ; id = â‰¡-refl ; comp = Î» {x y z p q} â†’ proof {x} {y} {z} {p} {q}
     }
     where
          toMap : âˆ€ {x y} â†’ x â‡ y â†’ ver f x âŸ¶ ver f y
          toMap (y !) = Id
          toMap (x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ p) = edge f e â¨¾ toMap p

          proof : âˆ€{x y z} {p : x â‡ y} {q : y â‡ z} â†’ toMap (p ++ q) â‰¡ toMap p â¨¾ toMap q
          proof {p = ._ !} = â‰¡-sym leftId
          proof {p = ._ âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ ps} = â‰¡-cong (Î» m â†’ edge f e â¨¾ m) (proof {p = ps}) âŸ¨â‰¡â‰¡âŸ© â‰¡-sym assoc
\end{code}
Now we have the embedding and the lifting, it remains to show that the aforementioned property
holds and so does uniqueness.

{\sc show that we have a natural transformation |Id âŸ¶ ğ’°â‚€ âˆ˜ ğ’«â‚€| }

%}}}

   %{{{ Equality
\begin{comment}
Before postulating extensionality, I used the following notions.

to talk of equations, we need appropriate equalitites

\begin{code}
  _â‰ˆg_ : âˆ€{G H : Graph} (f g : G âŸ¶ H) â†’ Set
  _â‰ˆg_ {G} {H} f g = Î£ veq âˆ¶ (âˆ€ {v} â†’ ver f v â‰¡ ver g v) â€¢
    (âˆ€ {x y e} â†’ edge g {x} {y} e â‰¡ â‰¡-substâ‚‚ (Î» a b â†’ Graph._âŸ¶_ H a b) veq veq (edge f {x} {y} e))

  _â‰‹_ : âˆ€{ğ’ ğ’Ÿ : Category} (f g : ğ’ âŸ¶ ğ’Ÿ) â†’ Set
  F â‰‹ G = ğ’°â‚ F â‰ˆg ğ’°â‚ G   -- proofs (x , y) now replaced with: funcext x y
\end{code}
Spelled-out:
\begin{spec}
