   %{{{ Another freedom proof
\subsection{Another freedom proof}

However, saying each graph-map gives rise to exactly one unique functor is tantamount to
saying the type |GraphMap G (ğ’°â‚€ ğ’)| is isomorphic to |Functor (ğ’«â‚€ G) ğ’|, that is
|(ğ’«â‚€ G âŸ¶ ğ’) â‰… (G âŸ¶ ğ’°â‚€ ğ’)| ---observe that this says we can `move' |ğ’«â‚€| from the left to
the right of an arrow at the cost of it (and the arrow) changing.

A few healthy excercises,
\begin{spec}
  liftË˜ : Functor ğ’«G ğ’ â†’ GraphMap G (ğ’°â‚€ ğ’)
  liftË˜ F = Î¹ â¨¾g ğ’°â‚ F -- i.e., |obj F , (mor F âˆ˜ edge Î¹)|

  rid : âˆ€{f : GraphMap G (ğ’°â‚€ ğ’)} â†’ âˆ€{x y} {e : x âŸ¶g y} â†’ liftË˜ (lift f) â‰¡ f
  rid = {! exercise !}

  lid : âˆ€{F : Functor ğ’«G ğ’} â†’ lift (liftË˜ F) â‰¡ F
  lid = {! exercise !}
\end{spec}
One can of course obtain these proofs from the other ones without recourse to definitions,
however for comprehension one would do well to prove them from first principles.
The worked out solutions are available in the literate source file of this document.

%{{{ worked out solutions
\begin{comment}
\begin{code}
  liftË˜ : Functor (ğ’«â‚€ G) ğ’ â†’ GraphMap G (ğ’°â‚€ ğ’)
  liftË˜ F = Î¹ â¨¾ ğ’°â‚ F -- |â‰¡ obj F # (mor F âˆ˜ edge Î¹)|
  
  ridâ‚€ : âˆ€ {f : GraphMap G (ğ’°â‚€ ğ’)} â†’ ver (liftË˜ (lift f)) â‰¡ ver f
  ridâ‚€ {f} = begin
      ver (liftË˜ (lift f))
    â‰¡âŸ¨âŸ© -- ver of liftË˜ ; defn of liftË˜
      obj (lift f)
    â‰¡âŸ¨âŸ© -- defn of lift.obj
      ver f
    âˆ
-- note that |â‰¡-refl| would have suffcied, but we show all the steps for clarity, for human consumption!

  open Graph G renaming (_âŸ¶_ to _âŸ¶g_)
  ridâ‚ : âˆ€{f : GraphMap G (ğ’°â‚€ ğ’)} â†’ âˆ€{x y} {e : x âŸ¶g y} â†’ edge (liftË˜ (lift f)) e â‰¡ edge f e
  ridâ‚ {f} {x} {y} {e} = begin
      edge (liftË˜ (lift f)) e
    â‰¡âŸ¨âŸ© -- |liftË˜.edge| definition
      mor (lift f) (edge Î¹ e)
    â‰¡âŸ¨âŸ© -- |lift.mor| on an edge; i.e., the inductive case of |toMap|
      edge f e â¨¾ Id
    â‰¡âŸ¨ rightId âŸ©
      edge f e
    âˆ
    -- without {{..}} I'd have to write |Category.Id ğ’| and |Category._â¨¾_ ğ’ â€¦| and |Category.rightId ğ’| above

  rid : âˆ€{f : GraphMap G (ğ’°â‚€ ğ’)} â†’ liftË˜ (lift f) â‰¡ f
  rid {f} = graphmapext â‰¡-refl (â‰¡-sym (ridâ‚ {f}))
  
  lidâ‚€ : âˆ€{F : Functor (ğ’«â‚€ G) ğ’} â†’ obj (lift (liftË˜ F)) â‰¡ obj F
  lidâ‚€ {F} =  begin
      obj (lift (liftË˜ F))
    â‰¡âŸ¨âŸ© -- obj of lift
      ver (liftË˜ F)
    â‰¡âŸ¨âŸ© -- ver of liftË˜
       obj F
    âˆ

  lidâ‚ : âˆ€{F : Functor (ğ’«â‚€ G) ğ’} â†’ âˆ€ {x y} {p : x â‡ y} â†’ mor (lift (liftË˜ F)) p â‰¡ mor F p
  lidâ‚ {F} {x} {.x} {p = (.x) !} = begin
      mor (lift (liftË˜ F)) (x !)
    â‰¡âŸ¨âŸ© -- mor of lift on !
      Id 
    â‰¡âŸ¨ â‰¡-sym (Functor.id F) âŸ© -- ! is identity path in |ğ’«G| and functtor preserve identites
       mor F (x !)
    âˆ
    
  lidâ‚ {F} {x} {y} {p = .x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ ps} = begin
      mor (lift (liftË˜ F)) (x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ ps)
    â‰¡âŸ¨âŸ© -- mor on lift on inductive case
      edge (liftË˜ F) e â¨¾ mor (lift (liftË˜ F)) ps
    â‰¡âŸ¨  â‰¡-cong (Î» w â†’ edge (liftË˜ F) e â¨¾ w) (lidâ‚ {F}) âŸ©
      edge (liftË˜ F) e â¨¾ mor F ps
    â‰¡âŸ¨âŸ© -- edge on liftË˜
      mor F (edge Î¹ e) â¨¾ mor F ps
    â‰¡âŸ¨ â‰¡-sym (Functor.comp F) âŸ© -- factor out Functor.mor
      mor F (edge Î¹ e ++ ps)
    â‰¡âŸ¨âŸ© -- defn of ++
      mor F (x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ ps)
    âˆ

  lid : âˆ€ {F : Functor (ğ’«â‚€ G) ğ’} â†’ lift (liftË˜ F) â‰¡ F
  lid  {F} = funcext â‰¡-refl (â‰¡-sym (lidâ‚ {F}))

  -- old version
  lift-â‰ˆ : âˆ€{f f' : GraphMap G (ğ’°â‚€ ğ’)} â†’ f â‰ˆg f' â†’ lift f â‰‹ lift f'
  lift-â‰ˆ  {f} {f'} (veq , eeq) = veq , (Î» {x} {y} {p} â†’ pf {x} {y} {p})
    where
      pf : {x y : V} {p : x â‡ y} â†’ mor (lift f') p â‰¡ â‰¡-substâ‚‚ _âŸ¶_ veq veq (mor (lift f) p)
      pf {x} {.x} {p = .x !} rewrite (veq {x}) = â‰¡-refl
      pf {x} {y} {p = .x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ ps} = begin 
           mor (lift f') (x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ ps)
         â‰¡âŸ¨âŸ©
           edge f' e â¨¾ mor (lift f') ps
         â‰¡âŸ¨ â‰¡-congâ‚‚ _â¨¾_ eeq (pf {p = ps}) âŸ©
           â‰¡-substâ‚‚ _âŸ¶_ veq veq (edge f e) â¨¾ â‰¡-substâ‚‚ _âŸ¶_ veq veq (mor (lift f) ps) 
         â‰¡âŸ¨ subst-dist veq x _ y âŸ©
            â‰¡-substâ‚‚ _âŸ¶_ veq veq (mor (lift f) (x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ ps))
         âˆ
\end{code}
\end{comment}
%}}}

We can then given an alternate proof of uniqueness |âˆ€{f h}â†’ f â‰¡ (Î¹ â¨¾ ğ’°â‚ h) â†’ lift f â‰¡ h|.
\begin{code}
  uniqueness' : âˆ€{f h}â†’ f â‰¡ (Î¹ â¨¾ ğ’°â‚ h) â†’ lift f â‰¡ h
  uniqueness' {f} {h} fâ‰ˆÎ¹â¨¾ğ’°â‚h = begin
      lift f
    â‰¡âŸ¨ â‰¡-cong lift fâ‰ˆÎ¹â¨¾ğ’°â‚h âŸ©
      lift (Î¹ â¨¾ ğ’°â‚ h)
    â‰¡âŸ¨ definition {- of |liftË˜| -} âŸ©
      lift (liftË˜ h)
    â‰¡âŸ¨ lid âŸ©
      h
    âˆ
\end{code}
%}}}

   %{{{ |ğ’« âŠ£ ğ’°| proof
\subsection{|ğ’« âŠ£ ğ’°|}
   %{{{ reasoning for naturality proof obligation
\begin{comment}
\begin{verbatim}
Following is probably full of type errors, since it's all by hand!

Anyhow, let's recall the notion of natural isomorphism, then apply it to adjunctions then to our
particular adjunction for paths.

|F â‰… G| means |âˆ€ A : Obj ğ’ â€¢ âˆƒ Î¦ : F A â‰… G A â€¢ âˆ€ X Y : Obj ğ’ â€¢ âˆ€ f : X âŸ¶ Y â€¢ F f â¨¾ Î¦ {Y} â‰ˆ Î¦ {X} â¨¾ G f|
Given f w e have two ways to get from F X to G Y:
first lift f to |F f : F X â†’ F Y| then shift to |F f â¨¾ Î¦ {Y} : F X â†’ G Y|,
alternatively we shift then lift to obtain |Î¦ {X} â¨¾ G f : F X â†’ G Y|
and ideally we'd like to avoid having to make a choise and so request
these two approaches to be the same.


For the case |F âŠ£ G|.

FF := F _ âŸ¶ _ : ğ’áµ’áµ–Ã—ğ’Ÿ â†’ ğ’Ÿ' : Î» (A , B) â†’ F A âŸ¶ B ; where ğ’Ÿ' is the cats of arrows of |ğ’Ÿ|.
                            : Î» (m : Mor ğ’, n : Mor ğ’Ÿ) â†’ Î» k : F (Tgt m) âŸ¶ğ’Ÿ Src n â†’ F m â¨¾ k â¨¾ n 


Given m : Xâ‚˜ âŸ¶ğ’ Yâ‚˜ and n : Xâ‚™ âŸ¶ğ’Ÿ Yâ‚™, we have |(m , n) : (Yâ‚˜ , Xâ‚™) âŸ¶ (Xâ‚˜ , Yâ‚™)| is an arrow of |ğ’áµ’áµ– Ã— ğ’Ÿ|.
we have FF (m , n) : (F Yâ‚˜ âŸ¶ğ’Ÿ Xâ‚™) â†’ (F Xâ‚˜ âŸ¶ğ’Ÿ Yâ‚™)
        Î¦ {A} {B} : (F A âŸ¶ğ’Ÿ B) â‰… (A âŸ¶ğ’ G B)
then
FF (m , n) â¨¾ Î¦ {Yâ‚˜} {Xâ‚™} : (F Yâ‚˜ âŸ¶ğ’Ÿ Xâ‚™) â†’ (Xâ‚˜ âŸ¶ğ’Ÿ G Yâ‚™) : k â†¦ Î¦ {Yâ‚˜} {Xâ‚™} (F m â¨¾ k â¨¾ n)

Likewise,
GG (m, n) : (Yâ‚˜ âŸ¶ğ’ G Xâ‚™) â†’ (Xâ‚˜ âŸ¶ğ’Ÿ G Yâ‚™) : k â†¦ m â¨¾ k â¨¾ G n
and thus
Î¦ {Xâ‚˜} {Yâ‚™} â¨¾ GG (m, n) : (F Yâ‚˜ âŸ¶ğ’Ÿ Xâ‚™) â†’ (Xâ‚˜ âŸ¶ğ’Ÿ G Yâ‚™) : k â†¦ m â¨¾ Î¦ {Yâ‚˜} {Xâ‚™} k â¨¾ G n

Hence we need,
|âˆ€ k : F Yâ‚˜ âŸ¶ğ’Ÿ Xâ‚™ â€¢ Î¦ {Yâ‚˜} {Xâ‚™} (F m â¨¾ k â¨¾ n) â‰ˆ m â¨¾ Î¦ {Yâ‚˜} {Xâ‚™} k â¨¾ G n|

For our case |ğ’« âŠ£ ğ’°|.
Naturality becomes, using |ğ’¢| for |ğ’¢ğ“‡ğ’¶ğ“…ğ’½| and |ğ’| for |ğ’ğ’¶ğ“‰|,
|âˆ€ G H : Obj ğ’¢ğ“‡ğ’¶ğ“…ğ’½ â€¢ âˆ€ ğ’ ğ’Ÿ : Obj ğ’ğ’¶ğ“‰ â€¢ âˆ€ g : GraphMap G H â€¢ âˆ€ F : Functor ğ’ ğ’Ÿ â€¢ 
âˆ€ k : Functor (ğ’« H) ğ’ â€¢ liftË˜ {G} {ğ’} (ğ’« g â¨¾ k â¨¾ F) â‰ˆ g â¨¾ liftË˜ {H} {ğ’} k â¨¾ ğ’° F|

That is, for every graph map g and functor F, for appropriate functor k we have
|liftË˜ (ğ’« g â¨¾ k â¨¾ F) â‰ˆ g â¨¾ liftË˜ k â¨¾ ğ’° F| in the category of graphs.
\end{verbatim}
\end{comment}
%}}}

That is, |ğ’« âŠ£ ğ’°| and say |ğ’«| is a `free-functor' since it is left-adjoint to a forgetful-functor.

We have
\begin{spec}
lift  : G âŸ¶ ğ’°â‚€ ğ’ â†’ ğ’«G âŸ¶ ğ’
liftË˜ : ğ’«G âŸ¶ ğ’ â†’ G âŸ¶ ğ’°â‚€ ğ’
\end{spec}
and we proved them to be inverses hence
|(ğ’«G âŸ¶ ğ’) â‰… (G âŸ¶ ğ’°â‚€ ğ’)|.

To realise |ğ’« âŠ£ ğ’°| it remains to exhibit `naturality':
for every graph map g and functor F, for appropriate functor k we have
|liftË˜ (ğ’« g â¨¾ k â¨¾ F) â‰ˆ g â¨¾ liftË˜ k â¨¾ ğ’° F| in the category of graphs.
\begin{code}
module _ {G H : Graph} {ğ’ ğ’Ÿ : Category {â„“â‚€} {â„“â‚€}} (g : GraphMap G H) (F : Functor ğ’ ğ’Ÿ) where

  private
    liftË˜ = Î» {A} {C} B â†’ freedom.liftË˜ A {C} B
    lift = Î» {A} {C} B â†’ freedom.lift A {C} B
  open Category {{...}}

  naturalityË˜ : âˆ€ {K : Functor (ğ’«â‚€ H) ğ’} â†’ liftË˜ (ğ’«â‚ g â¨¾ K â¨¾ F) â‰¡ (g â¨¾ liftË˜ K â¨¾ ğ’°â‚ F)
  naturalityË˜ = graphmapext â‰¡-refl â‰¡-refl
\end{code}
That was easier than assumed! haha ---much harder to formalize but so easy to prove lolz
It says we can `shunt' |liftË˜| into certain compositions at the cost
of replacing functor instances.

Just we needed to prove two inverse laws for |lift| and |liftË˜|, we need two naturality proofs.
\begin{code}
  naturality : âˆ€ {k : GraphMap H (ğ’°â‚€ ğ’)} â†’ lift (g â¨¾ k â¨¾ ğ’°â‚ F) â‰¡ (ğ’«â‚ g â¨¾ lift k â¨¾ F)
  naturality {k} = funcext â‰¡-refl (Î» {x y p} â†’ proof {x} {y} {p})
    where
      open TypedPaths {{...}}
      proof : âˆ€ {x y} {p : x â‡ y} â†’ mor (ğ’«â‚ g â¨¾ lift {H} {ğ’} k â¨¾ F) p â‰¡ mor (lift {G} {ğ’Ÿ} (g â¨¾ k â¨¾ ğ’°â‚ F)) p
      proof {x} {p = .x !} = functors-preserve-identities
      proof {x} {p = .x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ ps} = begin
            mor (ğ’«â‚ g â¨¾ lift {H} {ğ’} k â¨¾ F) (x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ ps)
         â‰¡âŸ¨ definition âŸ© 
            (mor (ğ’«â‚ g) â¨¾ mor (lift {H} {ğ’} k) â¨¾ mor F) (x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ ps)
         â‰¡âŸ¨ definition {- of function composition and |ğ’«â‚ â¨¾ mor| -} âŸ©
            mor F (mor (lift {H} {ğ’} k) (mor (ğ’«â‚ g) (x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ ps)))
         â‰¡âŸ¨ definition âŸ©
            mor F (mor (lift {H} {ğ’} k) (ver g x âŸ¶[ edge g e ]âŸ¶ mor (ğ’«â‚ g) ps))
         â‰¡âŸ¨ definition {-of |lift â¨¾ mor| on inductive case for paths -} âŸ©
            mor F (edge k (edge g e) â¨¾ mor (lift {H} {ğ’} k) (mor (ğ’«â‚ g) ps))
         â‰¡âŸ¨ functors-preserve-composition âŸ©
            mor F (edge k (edge g e)) â¨¾ mor F (mor (lift {H} {ğ’} k) (mor (ğ’«â‚ g) ps))
         â‰¡âŸ¨ definition {- of function composition -} âŸ©
            (edge g â¨¾ edge k â¨¾ mor F) e â¨¾ (mor (ğ’«â‚ g) â¨¾ mor (lift {H} {ğ’} k) â¨¾ mor F) ps
         â‰¡âŸ¨ {- |ğ’°â‚ â¨¾ edge = mor| and edge and mor are functorial by -} definition âŸ©
            edge (g â¨¾ k â¨¾ ğ’°â‚ F) e â¨¾ mor (ğ’«â‚ g â¨¾ lift {H} {ğ’} k â¨¾ F) ps
         â‰¡âŸ¨ {-inductive hypothesis: -} â‰¡-congâ‚‚ _â¨¾_ â‰¡-refl (proof {p = ps}) âŸ©
            edge (g â¨¾ k â¨¾ ğ’°â‚ F) e â¨¾ mor (lift {G} {ğ’Ÿ} (g â¨¾ k â¨¾ ğ’°â‚ F)) ps
         â‰¡âŸ¨ definition {-of |lift â¨¾ mor| on inductive case for paths -}âŸ©
            mor (lift {G} {ğ’Ÿ} (g â¨¾ k â¨¾ ğ’°â‚ F)) (x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ ps)
         âˆ
\end{code}

\href{http://maartenfokkinga.github.io/utwente/mmf92b.pdf}{Fokkinga [Theorem A.4]},
among others, would call
these laws `fusion' instead since they inform us how to compose, or `fuse', a morphism with a
|liftË˜|ed morphism: taking |F| to be the identity and remembering that functors preserve
identities, we have that |g â¨¾ liftË˜ K â‰¡ liftË˜( ğ’«â‚ g â¨¾ K)| --we can push a morphism into a |liftË˜|
at the cost of introducing a |ğ’«â‚|; dually for |lift|ed morphisms.

Formally,
\begin{code}
ğ’«âŠ£ğ’° : ğ’« âŠ£ ğ’°
ğ’«âŠ£ğ’° = record{
    âŒŠ_âŒ‹ = liftË˜
  ; âŒˆ_âŒ‰ = lift
  ; lid = lid
  ; rid = Î» {G ğ’ c} â†’ rid {G} {ğ’} {c}
  ; lfusion = Î» {G H ğ’ ğ’Ÿ f F K} â†’ naturalityË˜ {G} {H} {ğ’} {ğ’Ÿ} f K {F}
  ; rfusion = Î» {G H ğ’ ğ’Ÿ f k F} â†’ naturality {G} {H} {ğ’} {ğ’Ÿ} f F {k} }
  where
    module _ {G : Graph} {ğ’ : Category} where open freedom G {ğ’} public
\end{code}

%}}}

%}}}

%{{{ fold over paths
* {fold over paths}

Observe that for the freedom proof we recalled
that ists determine a form of quantification, `folding':
given an operation |âŠ•|, we may form |[xâ‚, â€¦, xâ‚–] â†¦ xâ‚ âŠ• â‹¯ âŠ• xâ‚–|.
Then used that to define our operation |lift|, whose core was essentially,
\begin{code}
module folding (G : Graph) where
  open TypedPaths G
  open Graph G
  
  fold : {X : Set} (v : V â†’ X) (f : âˆ€ x {y} (e : x âŸ¶ y) â†’ X â†’ X) â†’ (âˆ€ {a b} â†’ a â‡ b â†’ X)
  fold v f (b !) = v b
  fold v f (x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ ps) = f x e (fold v f ps)  
\end{code}          

For example, what is the length of a path?
\begin{code}
  length : âˆ€{x y} â†’ x â‡ y â†’ â„•
  length = fold (Î» _ â†’ 0)          -- single walks are length 0
                (Î» _ _ n â†’ 1 + n)  -- edges are one more than the length of the remaining walk
\end{code}
Let's verify that this is actually what we intend by the length of a path.
\begin{code}
  length-! : âˆ€{x} â†’ length (x !) â‰¡ 0
  length-! = â‰¡-refl   -- true by definition of |length|: the first argument to the |fold|

  length-ind : âˆ€ {x y Ï‰} {e : x âŸ¶ y} {ps : y â‡ Ï‰} â†’ length (x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ ps) â‰¡ 1 + length ps
  length-ind = â‰¡-refl -- true by definition of |length|: the second-argument to the |fold|
\end{code}

Generalzing on |length|, suppose we have a `cost function' |c| that assigns a cost of traversing
an edge. Then we can ask what is the total cost of a path:
\begin{code}
  path-cost : (c : âˆ€{x y}(e : x âŸ¶ y) â†’ â„•) â†’ âˆ€{x y}(ps : x â‡ y) â†’ â„•
  path-cost c = fold (Î» _ â†’ 0)           -- no cost on an empty path
                     (Î» x e n â†’ c e + n) -- cost of current edge plus cost of remainder of path
\end{code}
Now, we have BACKEND-ERROR %% |length = path-cost (Î» _ â†’ 1)|: length is just assigning a cost of 1 to each edge.

Under suitable conditions, list fold distributes over list concatenation, can we find an analogue
for paths?
\begin{code}
  fold-++ :  âˆ€{X : Set} {v : V â†’ X} {g : âˆ€ x {y} (e : x âŸ¶ y) â†’ X}
          â†’ (_âŠ•_ : X â†’ X â†’ X)
          â†’ âˆ€{x y z : V} {p : x â‡ y} {q : y â‡ z}
          â†’ (unitl : âˆ€{x y} â†’ y â‰¡ v x âŠ• y)                    -- image of |v| is left unit of |âŠ•|
          â†’ (assoc : âˆ€ {x y z} â†’ x âŠ• (y âŠ• z) â‰¡ (x âŠ• y) âŠ• z )  -- |âŠ•| is associative 
          â†’ let f : âˆ€ x {y} (e : x âŸ¶ y) â†’ X â†’ X
                f = Î» x e ps â†’ g x e âŠ• ps
             in
               fold v f (p ++ q) â‰¡ fold v f p âŠ• fold v f q
  fold-++ {g = g} _âŠ•_ {x = x} {p = .x !} unitl assoc =  unitl
  fold-++ {g = g} _âŠ•_ {x = x} {p = .x âŸ¶[ e ]âŸ¶ ps} unitl assoc =
    â‰¡-cong (Î» exp â†’ g x e âŠ• exp) (fold-++ _âŠ•_ {p = ps} unitl assoc) âŸ¨â‰¡â‰¡âŸ© assoc
\end{code}

Compare this with the proof-obligation of |lift|.

%}}}

%{{{ Lists are special kinds of paths
\subsection{Lists are special kinds of paths}
We called our path concatenation BACKEND-ERROR %% |_++_|, why the same symbol as that for list concatenation?

How do we interpret a list over |A| as graph? Well the vertices can be any element of |A|
and an edge |x âŸ¶ y| merely indicates that ``the item after |x| in the list is the element |y|'',
so we want it to be always true; or always inhabited without distinction of the inhabitant:
so use a unit type.
\begin{code}
module lists (A : Set) where

  open import Data.Unit

  listGraph : Graph
  listGraph = record { V = A ; _âŸ¶_ = Î» a a' â†’ âŠ¤ }
\end{code}
I haven't a clue if this works, you read my reasoning above.

The only thing we can do is test our hypothesis by looking at the typed paths over this graph.
In particular, we attempt to show every non-empty list of |A|'s corresponds to a path.
Since a typed path needs a priori the start and end vertes, let us construe
|List A â‰… Î£ n âˆ¶ â„• â€¢ Fin n â†’ A| --later note that |Path G â‰… Î£ n âˆ¶ â„• â€¢ [n] ğ’¢âŸ¶ G|--.
\begin{code}
  open TypedPaths listGraph
  open folding listGraph

  -- every non-empty list of 'A's corresonds to a path!
  toPath : âˆ€{n} (list : Fin (suc n) â†’ A) â†’  list fzero  â‡ list ( fromâ„• n )
  toPath {zero} list = list fzero !
  toPath {suc n} list = list fzero âŸ¶[ tt ]âŸ¶ toPath {n} (Î» i â†’ list(fsuc i))
    -- note that |list : Fin (suc (suc n)) â†’ A| while |suc â¨¾ list : Fin (suc n) â†’ A|
    
  -- if | list â‰ˆ [x , y , z] | then
  -- |fsuc â¨¾ list â‰ˆ [y , z ] |
  -- |fsuc â¨¾ fsuc â¨¾ list = [z] |
\end{code}
Hm! Look at that, first guess and it worked! Sweet.

Now let's realize the list fold as an instance of path fold,
\begin{code}
  -- list type former
  List = Î» (X : Set) â†’ Î£ n âˆ¶ â„• â€¢ (Fin n â†’ X)

  -- usual list folding
  foldr : âˆ€{B : Set} (f : A â†’ B â†’ B) (e : B) â†’ List A â†’ B
  foldr f e (zero , l) = e
  foldr f e (suc n , l) = fold (Î» a â†’ f a e) (Î» a _ rem â†’ f a rem) (toPath l)

  -- example
  listLength : List A â†’ â„• -- result should clearly be |projâ‚| of the list, anyhow:
  listLength = foldr (Î» a rem â†’ 1 + rem) -- non-empty list has length 1 more than the remainder
                     0                    -- empty list has length 0

  -- let's prepare for a more useful example

  -- empty list
  [] : âˆ€{X : Set} â†’ List X
  [] = 0 , Î» ()

  -- cons for lists
  _âˆ·_ : âˆ€{X : Set} â†’ X â†’ List X â†’ List X
  _âˆ·_ {X} x (n , l) = 1 + n , cons x l
    where
      -- |cons a l â‰¡ Î» i : Fin (1 + n) â†’ if i â‰ˆ 0 then a else l i|
      cons : âˆ€{n} â†’ X â†’ (Fin n â†’ X) â†’ (Fin (suc n) â†’ X)
      cons x l fzero = x
      cons x l (fsuc i) = l i
  
  map : âˆ€ {B} (f : A â†’ B) â†’ List A â†’ List B
  map f =  foldr (Î» a rem â†’ f a âˆ· rem) []  -- looks like the usual map don't it ;)

  -- list concatenation
  _++â„“_ : List A â†’ List A â†’ List A
  l ++â„“ r = foldr _âˆ·_ r l -- fold over |l| by cons its elements infront of |r|

  -- Exercise: write path concatenation as a path-fold.
\end{code}
%}}}

This note took longer to write than I had initally assumed; perhaps I should have taken into
account Hofstadter's Law, which says:
"It always takes longer than you expect, even when you take into account Hofstadter's Law.".

